# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: animal-assisted-therapy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] While research has demonstrated that thinking and behavior may be altered in virtually all forms of ABI, brain injury is itself a very complex phenomenon having dramatically varied effects.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] No two persons can expect the same outcome or resulting difficulties.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] The brain controls every part of human life: physical, intellectual, behavioral, social and emotional.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] When the brain is damaged, some part of a person's life will be adversely affected.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] Advances in emergency medicine and critical care have increased survival rates among brain injury populations, leading to a growing number of individuals living with chronic disabilities after sustaining brain injury.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] Reviews emphasize the importance of proper rehabilitation and community support for these individuals.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] Consequences of ABI often require a major life adjustment around the person's new circumstances, and making that adjustment is a critical factor in recovery and rehabilitation.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] While the outcome of a given injury depends largely upon the nature and severity of the injury itself, appropriate treatment plays a vital role in determining the level of recovery.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] ABI has been associated with a number of emotional difficulties such as depression, issues with self-control, managing anger impulses and challenges with problem-solving, these challenges also contribute to psychosocial concerns involving social anxiety, loneliness and lower levels of self esteem.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] These psychosocial problems have been found to contribute to other dilemmas such as reduced frequency of social contact and leisure activities, unemployment, family problems and marital difficulties.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] How the patient copes with the injury has been found to influence the level at which they experience the emotional complications correlated with ABI.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] Three coping strategies for emotions related to ABI have presented themselves in the research, approach-oriented coping, passive coping and avoidant coping.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] Approach-oriented coping has been found to be the most effective strategy, as it has been negatively correlated with rates of apathy and depression in ABI patients; this coping style is present in individuals who consciously work to minimize the emotional challenges of ABI.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] Passive coping has been characterized by the person choosing not to express emotions and a lack of motivation which can lead to poor outcomes for the individual.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] Increased levels of depression have been correlated to avoidance coping methods in patients with ABI; this strategy is represented in people who actively evade coping with emotions.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] These challenges and coping strategies should be kept in consideration when seeking to understand individuals with ABI.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] Following acquired brain injury it is common for people to experience memory loss; memory disorders are one of the most prevalent cognitive deficits experienced in affected people.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] However, because some aspects of memory are directly linked to attention, it can be challenging to assess what components of a deficit are caused by memory and which are fundamentally attention problems.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] There is often partial recovery of memory functioning following the initial recovery phase; however, permanent handicaps are often reported with ABI patients reporting significantly more memory difficulties when compared people without an acquired brain injury.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] In order to cope more efficiently with memory disorders many people with ABI use memory aids; these included external items such as diaries, notebooks and electronic organizers, internal strategies such as visual associations, and environmental adaptations such as labelling kitchen cupboards.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] Research has found that ABI patients use an increased number of memory aids after their injury than they did prior to it and these aids vary in their degree of effectiveness.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] Studies have found that the use of a diary is more effective if it is paired with self-instructional training, as training leads to more frequent use of the diary over time and thus more successful use as a memory aid.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] Relations to Acquired Brain injury can occur in a variety of ways.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] In adults aged 65 plus, 82.9% of hospitalizations were related to falls, about 13% experienced death shortly after.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] Furthermore, transportation related accidents were around 9% in correlation to brain injury.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] The number of hospitalizations related to brain injury is only increasing as well.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] Tripping, slipping, or stumbling is one of the biggest ways of experiencing these brain related injuries.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] Additionally, an acquired brain injury can happen due to anoxia.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] This is often caused by carbon monoxide poisoning or drowning, as the lack of oxygen in these situations causes cell death.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] Rehabilitation following an acquired brain injury does not follow a set protocol, due to the variety of mechanisms of injury and structures affected.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] Rather, rehabilitation is an individualized process that will often involve a multi-disciplinary approach.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] The rehabilitation team may include but is not limited to nurses, neurologists, physiotherapists, psychiatrists (particularly those specialized in Brain Injury Medicine), occupational therapists, speech-language pathologists, music therapists, and rehabilitation psychologists.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] Physical therapy and other professions may be utilized post- brain injury in order to control muscle tone, regain normal movement patterns, and maximize functional independence.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] Rehabilitation should be patient-centered and guided by the individual's needs and goals.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] Research in physical medicine and rehabilitation call attention to the importance of timing, intensity, and continuity of therapy after acquired brain injury.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] Systematic reviews have shown that rehabilitation through coordinated programs such as inpatient rehabilitation centers are associated with improved functional outcomes compared to those with less organized care.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] Outcomes are improved when therapies are persistent over time as well.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] However, outcomes vary among individuals and studies emphasize the difficulties in comparing results due to differences in injury severity, treatment settings, comorbidities, and outcome measures.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] Rehabilitation outcomes are commonly measured through functional status such as level of independence when performing everyday activities and return-to-work rates.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] This is how the effectiveness of different rehabilitation programs are evaluated.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] Long-term follow up is usually required after acquired brain injury because functional recovery may continue for months or years after the injury.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] There is some evidence that rhythmic auditory stimulation is beneficial in gait rehabilitation following a brain injury.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] Music therapy may assist patients to improve gait, arm swing while walking, communication, and quality of life after experiencing a stroke.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] Newer treatment methods such as virtual reality and robotics remain under-researched; however, there is reason to believe that virtual reality in upper limb rehabilitation may be useful, following an acquired brain injury.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] Due to few random control trials and generally weak evidence, more research is needed to gain a complete understanding of the ideal type and parameters of therapeutic interventions for treatment of acquired brain injuries.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] For more information on therapeutic interventions for acquired brain injury, see stroke and traumatic brain injury.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] Some strategies for rehabilitating the memory of those affected by ABI have used repetitive tasks to attempt to increase the patients' ability to recall information.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] While this type of training increases performance on the task at hand, there is little evidence that the skills translate to improved performance on memory challenges outside of the laboratory.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] These have been shown to increase memory functioning in patients based on self-report measures.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] Another strategy for improvement amongst individuals with poor memory functioning is the use of elaboration to improve encoding of items, one form of this strategy is called self-imagining whereby the patient imagines the event to be recalled from a more personal perspective.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] Self-imagining has been found to improve recognition memory by coding the event in a manner that is more individually salient to the subject.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] This effect has been found to improve recall in individuals with and without memory disorders.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] There is research evidence to suggest that rehabilitation programs that are geared toward the individual may have greater results than group-based interventions for improving memory in ABI patients because they are tailored to the symptoms experienced by the individual.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] More research is necessary in order to draw conclusions on how to improve memory among individuals with ABI that experience memory loss.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] Involvement in social situations is important for the normal development of children as a means of gaining an understanding of how to effectively work together with others.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] Furthermore, young people with ABI are often reported as having insufficient problem solving skills.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] This has the potential to hinder their performance in various academic and social settings further.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/acquired-brain-injury] It is important for rehabilitation programs to deal with these challenges specific to children who have not fully developed at the time of their injury.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Some alternative practices are based on theories that contradict the established science of how the human body works; others appeal to the supernatural or superstitions to explain their effect or lack thereof.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] In others, the practice has plausibility but lacks a positive risk–benefit outcome probability.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Research into alternative therapies often fails to follow proper research protocols (such as placebo-controlled trials, blind experiments and calculation of prior probability), providing invalid results.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] History has shown that if a method is proven to work, it eventually ceases to be alternative and becomes mainstream medicine.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Much of the perceived effect of an alternative practice arises from a belief that it will be effective, the placebo effect, or from the treated condition resolving on its own (the natural course of disease).
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] This is further exacerbated by the tendency to turn to alternative therapies upon the failure of medicine, at which point the condition will be at its worst and most likely to spontaneously improve.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] In the absence of this bias, especially for diseases that are not expected to get better by themselves such as cancer or HIV infection, multiple studies have shown significantly worse outcomes if patients turn to alternative therapies.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] While this may be because these patients avoid effective treatment, some alternative therapies are actively harmful (such as cyanide poisoning from amygdalin, or the intentional ingestion of hydrogen peroxide) or actively interfere with effective treatments.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] The alternative medicine sector is a highly profitable industry with a strong lobby, and faces far less regulation over the use and marketing of unproven treatments.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] **Complementary medicine** (**CM**), **complementary and alternative medicine** (**CAM**), **functional medicine** (**FM**), **integrated medicine** or **integrative medicine** (**IM**), and **holistic medicine** attempt to combine alternative practices with those of mainstream medicine.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Traditional medicine practices become "alternative" when used outside their original settings and without proper scientific explanation and evidence.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Alternative methods are often marketed as more "natural" or "holistic" than methods offered by medical science, that is sometimes derogatorily called "Big Pharma" by supporters of alternative medicine.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Billions of dollars have been spent studying alternative medicine, with few or no positive results and many methods thoroughly disproven.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Terminology has shifted over time, reflecting the preferred branding of practitioners.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Therapies are often framed as "natural" or "holistic", implicitly and intentionally suggesting that conventional medicine is "artificial" and "narrow in scope".
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] The meaning of the term "alternative" in the expression "alternative medicine", is not that it is an effective alternative to medical science (though some alternative medicine promoters may use the loose terminology to give the appearance of effectiveness).
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] "Biomedicine" or "medicine" is that part of medical science that applies principles of biology, physiology, molecular biology, biophysics, and other natural sciences to clinical practice, using scientific methods to establish the effectiveness of that practice.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Unlike medicine, an alternative product or practice does not originate from using scientific methods, but may instead be based on hearsay, religion, tradition, superstition, belief in supernatural energies, pseudoscience, errors in reasoning, propaganda, fraud, or other unscientific sources.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Some other definitions seek to specify alternative medicine in terms of its social and political marginality to mainstream healthcare.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] This can refer to the lack of support that alternative therapies receive from medical scientists regarding access to research funding, sympathetic coverage in the medical press, or inclusion in the standard medical curriculum.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] For example, a widely used definition devised by the National Center for Complementary and Alternative Medicine (NCCIH) calls it "a group of diverse medical and health care systems, practices, and products that are not generally considered part of conventional medicine".
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Some mainstream academic medical centers have integrative or functional medicine departments, including the Cleveland Clinic, the Mayo Clinic, Stanford University, UCLA, UC San Francisco and Northwestern University.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] In contrast, other medical practitioners are unconvinced by these practices.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] For example, surgical oncologist, David Gorski has described integrative medicine as an attempt to bring pseudoscience into academic science-based medicine with skeptics such as Gorski and David Colquhoun referring to this with the pejorative term "quackademia".
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Robert Todd Carroll described integrative medicine as "a synonym for 'alternative' medicine that, at its worst, integrates sense with nonsense.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] At its best, integrative medicine supports both consensus treatments of science-based medicine and treatments that the science, while promising perhaps, does not justify." Rose Shapiro has criticized the field of alternative medicine for rebranding the same practices as integrative medicine.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] CAM is an acronym for *complementary and alternative medicine*.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Functional medicine (FM) is a form of alternative medicine that encompasses many unproven and disproven methods and treatments.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] It is a rebranding of complementary and alternative medicine (CAM), and as such is pseudoscientific, and has been described as a form of quackery.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] In the US, FM practices have been ruled ineligible for course credits by the American Academy of Family Physicians because of concerns they may be harmful.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Functional medicine was created by Jeffrey Bland, who founded The Institute for Functional Medicine (IFM), which is based in the US state of Washington, in the early 1990s as part of one of his companies, HealthComm.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] IFM, which promotes functional medicine, became a registered non-profit in 2001.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Mark Hyman became an IFM board member and prominent promoter.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] David Gorski, a surgical oncologist at Wayne State University, has written that FM is not well-defined and performs "expensive and generally unnecessary tests".
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Gorski says FM's vagueness is a deliberate tactic that makes functional medicine difficult to challenge.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] These are meant to correspond to the underlying causes of health issues, the immediate causes, and the particular characteristics of a person's illness.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] A functional medicine practitioner devises a "matrix" from these factors to serve as the basis for treatment.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Treatments, practices, and concepts are generally not supported by medical evidence.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Patients of functional medicine practitioners may also be told to undertake unnecessary diets that can limit food choices.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] In the 1990s, integrative medicine started to be marketed by a new term, "functional medicine".
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] FM practitioners claim to diagnose and treat conditions that have been found by research studies not to exist, such as adrenal fatigue and numerous imbalances in body chemistry.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] For instance, contrary to scientific evidence, Joe Pizzorno, a major figure in FM, claimed that 25% of people in the United States have heavy metal poisoning and need to undergo detoxification.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Many scientists state that such detox supplements are a waste of time and money.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Detox has been also called "mass delusion".
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] In 2014, the American Academy of Family Physicians withdrew course credits for functional medicine courses, having identified some of its treatments as "harmful and dangerous".
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] In 2018, it partly lifted the ban, but only to allow overview classes, not to teach its practice.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] The opening of centers for functional medicine at the Cleveland Clinic and George Washington University was described by David Gorski as an "unfortunate" example of "quackademia" — that is, a quackery infiltrating academic medical centers.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Traditional medicine (TM) refers to certain practices within a culture which have existed since before the advent of medical science, Many TM practices are based on "holistic" approaches to disease and health, versus the scientific evidence-based methods in conventional medicine.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Others say that alternative medicine cannot be precisely defined because of the diversity of theories and practices it includes, and because the boundaries between alternative and conventional medicine overlap, are porous, and change.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Healthcare practices categorized as alternative may differ in their historical origin, theoretical basis, diagnostic technique, therapeutic practice and in their relationship to the medical mainstream.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Under a definition of alternative medicine as "non-mainstream", treatments considered alternative in one location may be considered conventional in another.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] There's only medicine that works and medicine that doesn't.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Alternative medicine consists of a wide range of health care practices, products, and therapies.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] The shared feature is a claim to heal that is not based on the scientific method.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Alternative medicine practices are diverse in their foundations and methodologies.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Alternative medicine practices may be classified by their cultural origins or by the types of beliefs upon which they are based.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Different cultures may have their own unique traditional or belief based practices developed recently or over thousands of years, and specific practices or entire systems of practices.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Alternative medicine, such as using naturopathy or homeopathy in place of conventional medicine, is based on belief systems not grounded in science.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Alternative medical systems may be based on traditional medicine practices, such as traditional Chinese medicine (TCM), Ayurveda in India, or practices of other cultures around the world.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Some useful applications of traditional medicines have been researched and accepted within ordinary medicine, however the underlying belief systems are seldom scientific and are not accepted.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Bases of belief may include belief in existence of supernatural energies undetected by the science of physics, as in biofields, or in belief in properties of the energies of physics that are inconsistent with the laws of physics, as in energy medicine.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Substance based practices use substances found in nature such as herbs, foods, non-vitamin supplements and megavitamins, animal and fungal products, and minerals, including use of these products in traditional medical practices that may also incorporate other methods.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Examples include healing claims for non-vitamin supplements, fish oil, Omega-3 fatty acid, glucosamine, echinacea, flaxseed oil, and ginseng.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Herbal medicine, or phytotherapy, includes not just the use of plant products, but may also include the use of animal and mineral products.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] It is among the most commercially successful branches of alternative medicine, and includes the tablets, powders and elixirs that are sold as "nutritional supplements".
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Only a very small percentage of these have been shown to have any efficacy, and there is little regulation as to standards and safety of their contents.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] The United States agency National Center for Complementary and Integrative Health (NCCIH) has created a classification system for branches of complementary and alternative medicine that divides them into five major groups.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] These groups have some overlap, and distinguish two types of energy medicine: *veritable* which involves scientifically observable energy (including magnet therapy, colorpuncture and light therapy) and *putative*, which invokes physically undetectable or unverifiable energy.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] None of these energies have any evidence to support that they affect the body in any positive or health promoting way.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Mind-body interventions: Explore the interconnection between the mind, body, and spirit, under the premise that they affect "bodily functions and symptoms".
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] A connection between mind and body is conventional medical fact, and this classification does not include therapies with proven function such as cognitive behavioral therapy.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] "Biology"-based practices: Use substances found in nature such as herbs, foods, vitamins, and other natural substances.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] (As used here, "biology" does *not* refer to the science of biology, but is a usage newly coined by NCCIH in the primary source used for this article.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Manipulative and body-based practices: feature manipulation or movement of body parts, such as is done in bodywork, chiropractic, and osteopathic manipulation.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] It includes the histories of complementary medicine and of integrative medicine.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Before the 1970s, western practitioners that were not part of the increasingly science-based medical establishment were referred to "irregular practitioners", and were dismissed by the medical establishment as unscientific and as practicing quackery.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Until the 1970s, irregular practice became increasingly marginalized as quackery and fraud, as western medicine increasingly incorporated scientific methods and discoveries, and had a corresponding increase in success of its treatments.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] In the 1970s, irregular practices were grouped with traditional practices of nonwestern cultures and with other unproven or disproven practices that were not part of biomedicine, with the entire group collectively marketed and promoted under the single expression "alternative medicine".
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Use of alternative medicine in the west began to rise following the counterculture movement of the 1960s, as part of the rising new age movement of the 1970s.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] At the same time, in 1975, the American Medical Association, which played the central role in fighting quackery in the United States, abolished its quackery committee and closed down its Department of Investigation.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] By the early to mid 1970s the expression "alternative medicine" came into widespread use, and the expression became mass marketed as a collection of "natural" and effective treatment "alternatives" to science-based biomedicine.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Changes included relaxed medical licensing, the development of managed care, rising consumerism, and the establishment of the USA Office of Alternative Medicine (later National Center for Complementary and Alternative Medicine, currently National Center for Complementary and Integrative Health).
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Mainly as a result of reforms following the Flexner Report of 1910 medical education in established medical schools in the US has generally not included alternative medicine as a teaching topic.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Typically, their teaching is based on current practice and scientific knowledge about: anatomy, physiology, histology, embryology, neuroanatomy, pathology, pharmacology, microbiology and immunology.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Medical schools' teaching includes such topics as doctor-patient communication, ethics, the art of medicine, and engaging in complex clinical reasoning (medical decision-making).
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Writing in 2002, Snyderman and Weil remarked that by the early twentieth century the Flexner model had helped to create the 20th-century academic health center, in which education, research, and practice were inseparable.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] By 2001 some form of CAM training was being offered by at least 75 out of 125 medical schools in the US.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Exceptionally, the School of Medicine of the University of Maryland, Baltimore, includes a research institute for integrative medicine (a member entity of the Cochrane Collaboration).
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Medical schools are responsible for conferring medical degrees, but a physician typically may not legally practice medicine until licensed by the local government authority.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Licensed physicians in the US who have attended one of the established medical schools there have usually graduated Doctor of Medicine (MD).
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] All states require that applicants for MD licensure be graduates of an approved medical school and complete the United States Medical Licensing Examination (USMLE).
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] There is a general scientific consensus that alternative therapies lack the requisite scientific validation, and their effectiveness is either unproved or disproved.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Many of the claims regarding the efficacy of alternative medicines are controversial, since research on them is frequently of low quality and methodologically flawed.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Selective publication bias, marked differences in product quality and standardisation, and some companies making unsubstantiated claims call into question the claims of efficacy of isolated examples where there is evidence for alternative therapies.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] In 2003, a project funded by the CDC identified 208 condition-treatment pairs, of which 58% had been studied by at least one randomized controlled trial (RCT), and 23% had been assessed with a meta-analysis.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] According to a 2005 book by a US Institute of Medicine panel, the number of RCTs focused on CAM has risen dramatically.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] As of 2005, the Cochrane Library had 145 CAM-related Cochrane systematic reviews and 340 non-Cochrane systematic reviews.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] An analysis of the conclusions of only the 145 Cochrane reviews was done by two readers.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] In 83% of the cases, the readers agreed.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] In the 17% in which they disagreed, a third reader agreed with one of the initial readers to set a rating.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] These studies found that, for CAM, 38.4% concluded positive effect or possibly positive (12.4%), 4.8% concluded no effect, 0.7% concluded harmful effect, and 56.6% concluded insufficient evidence.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] An assessment of conventional treatments found that 41.3% concluded positive or possibly positive effect, 20% concluded no effect, 8.1% concluded net harmful effects, and 21.3% concluded insufficient evidence.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] However, the CAM review used the more developed 2004 Cochrane database, while the conventional review used the initial 1998 Cochrane database.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Alternative therapies do not "complement" (improve the effect of, or mitigate the side effects of) functional medical treatment.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Significant drug interactions caused by alternative therapies may instead negatively impact functional treatment by making prescription drugs less effective, such as interference by herbal preparations with warfarin.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] In the same way as for conventional therapies, drugs, and interventions, it can be difficult to test the efficacy of alternative medicine in clinical trials.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] In instances where an established, effective, treatment for a condition is already available, the Helsinki Declaration states that withholding such treatment is unethical in most circumstances.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Use of standard-of-care treatment in addition to an alternative technique being tested may produce confounded or difficult-to-interpret results.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Anything classified as alternative medicine by definition does not have a proven healing or medical effect.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] However, there are different mechanisms through which it can be perceived to "work".
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] The common denominator of these mechanisms is that effects are mis-attributed to the alternative treatment.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] A placebo is a treatment with no intended therapeutic value.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] An example of a placebo is an inert pill, but it can include more dramatic interventions like sham surgery.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] The *placebo effect* is the concept that patients will perceive an improvement after being treated with an inert treatment.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] The opposite of the placebo effect is the *nocebo effect*, when patients who expect a treatment to be harmful will perceive harmful effects after taking it.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Placebos do not have a physical effect on diseases or improve overall outcomes, but patients may report improvements in subjective outcomes such as pain and nausea.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] A 1955 study suggested that a substantial part of a medicine's impact was due to the placebo effect.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] However, reassessments found the study to have flawed methodology.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] This and other modern reviews suggest that other factors like natural recovery and reporting bias should also be considered.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] All of these are reasons why alternative therapies may be credited for improving a patient's condition even though the objective effect is non-existent, or even harmful.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] David Gorski argues that alternative treatments should be treated as a placebo, rather than as medicine.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Almost none have performed significantly better than a placebo in clinical trials.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Furthermore, distrust of conventional medicine may lead to patients experiencing the nocebo effect when taking effective medication.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] A patient who receives an inert treatment may report improvements afterwards that it did not cause.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] Assuming it was the cause without evidence is an example of the regression fallacy.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] This may be due to a natural recovery from the illness, or a fluctuation in the symptoms of a long-term condition.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] The concept of regression toward the mean implies that an extreme result is more likely to be followed by a less extreme result.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] There are also reasons why a placebo treatment group may outperform a "no-treatment" group in a test which are not related to a patient's experience.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] These include patients reporting more favourable results than they really felt due to politeness or "experimental subordination", observer bias, and misleading wording of questions.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p01] In their 2010 systematic review of studies into placebos, Asbjørn Hróbjartsson and Peter C.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Practitioners of complementary medicine usually discuss and advise patients as to available alternative therapies.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Patients often express interest in mind-body complementary therapies because they offer a non-drug approach to treating some health conditions.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] In a 2018 interview with *The BMJ*, Edzard Ernst stated: "The present popularity of complementary and alternative medicine is also inviting criticism of what we are doing in mainstream medicine.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] It shows that we aren't fulfilling a certain need-we are not giving patients enough time, compassion, or empathy.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] These are things that complementary practitioners are very good at.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Alternative medicine is a profitable industry with large media advertising expenditures.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Accordingly, alternative practices are often portrayed positively and compared favorably to "big pharma".
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Paul Offit proposed that "alternative medicine becomes quackery" in four ways: by recommending against conventional therapies that are helpful, promoting potentially harmful therapies without adequate warning, draining patients' bank accounts, or by promoting "magical thinking".
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Promoting alternative medicine has been called dangerous and unethical.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Authors have speculated on the socio-cultural and psychological reasons for the appeal of alternative medicines among the minority using them *in lieu* of conventional medicine.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] There are several socio-cultural reasons for the interest in these treatments centered on the low level of scientific literacy among the public at large and a concomitant increase in antiscientific attitudes and new age mysticism.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Related to this are vigorous marketing of extravagant claims by the alternative medical community combined with inadequate media scrutiny and attacks on critics.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Alternative medicine is criticized for taking advantage of the least fortunate members of society.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Many patients lack access to contemporary medicine, due to a lack of private or public health insurance, which leads them to seek out lower-cost alternative medicine.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Medical doctors are also aggressively marketing alternative medicine to profit from this market.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Patients can be averse to the painful, unpleasant, and sometimes-dangerous side effects of biomedical treatments.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Treatments for severe diseases such as cancer and HIV infection have well-known, significant side-effects.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Even low-risk medications such as antibiotics can have potential to cause life-threatening anaphylactic reactions in a very few individuals.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Many medications may cause minor but bothersome symptoms such as cough or upset stomach.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] In all of these cases, patients may be seeking out alternative therapies to avoid the adverse effects of conventional treatments.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] According to research published in 2015, the increasing popularity of CAM needs to be explained by moral convictions or lifestyle choices rather than by economic reasoning.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] In developing nations, access to essential medicines is severely restricted by lack of resources and poverty.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Traditional remedies, often closely resembling or forming the basis for alternative remedies, may comprise primary healthcare or be integrated into the healthcare system.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] In Africa, traditional medicine is used for 80% of primary healthcare, and in developing nations as a whole over one-third of the population lack access to essential medicines.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] In Latin America, inequities against BIPOC communities keep them tied to their traditional practices and therefore, it is often these communities that constitute the majority of users of alternative medicine.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Racist attitudes towards certain communities disable them from accessing more urbanized modes of care.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] In a study that assessed access to care in rural communities of Latin America, it was found that discrimination is a huge barrier to the ability of citizens to access care; more specifically, women of Indigenous and African descent, and lower-income families were especially hurt.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Such exclusion exacerbates the inequities that minorities in Latin America already face.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Consistently excluded from many systems of westernized care for socioeconomic and other reasons, low-income communities of color often turn to traditional medicine for care as it has proved reliable to them across generations.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Commentators including David Horrobin have proposed adopting a prize system to reward medical research.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] This stands in opposition to the current mechanism for funding research proposals in most countries around the world.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] In the US, the NCCIH provides public research funding for alternative medicine.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] The NCCIH has spent more than US$2.5 billion on such research since 1992 and this research has not demonstrated the efficacy of alternative therapies.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] As of 2011, the NCCIH's sister organization in the NIH Office of Cancer Complementary and Alternative Medicine had given out grants of around $105 million each year for several years.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Testing alternative medicine that has no scientific basis (as in the aforementioned grants) has been called a waste of scarce research resources.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] That alternative medicine has been on the rise "in countries where Western science and scientific method generally are accepted as the major foundations for healthcare, and 'evidence-based' practice is the dominant paradigm" was described as an "enigma" in the *Medical Journal of Australia*.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] A 15-year systematic review published in 2022 on the global acceptance and use of CAM among medical specialists found the overall acceptance of CAM at 52% and the overall use at 45%.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] In the United States, the 1974 Child Abuse Prevention and Treatment Act (CAPTA) required that for states to receive federal money, they had to grant religious exemptions to child neglect and abuse laws regarding religion-based healing practices.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Thirty-one states have child-abuse religious exemptions.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] The use of alternative medicine in the US has increased, with a 50 percent increase in expenditures and a 25 percent increase in the use of alternative therapies between 1990 and 1997 in America.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] According to a national survey conducted in 2002, "36 percent of U.S. adults aged 18 years and over use some form of complementary and alternative medicine." Americans spend many billions on the therapies annually.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Most Americans used CAM to treat and/or prevent musculoskeletal conditions or other conditions associated with chronic or recurring pain.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] In America, women were more likely than men to use CAM, with the biggest difference in use of mind-body therapies including prayer specifically for health reasons".
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] In 2008, more than 37% of American hospitals offered alternative therapies, up from 27 percent in 2005, and 25% in 2004.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] More than 70% of the hospitals offering CAM were in urban areas.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] A survey of Americans found that 88 percent thought that "there are some good ways of treating sickness that medical science does not recognize".
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Use of magnets was the most common tool in energy medicine in America, and among users of it, 58 percent described it as at least "sort of scientific", when it is not at all scientific.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] In 2002, at least 60 percent of US medical schools have at least some class time spent teaching alternative therapies.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] "Therapeutic touch" was taught at more than 100 colleges and universities in 75 countries before the practice was debunked by a nine-year-old child for a school science project.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] The most common CAM therapies used in the US in 2002 were prayer (45%), herbalism (19%), breathing meditation (12%), meditation (8%), chiropractic medicine (8%), yoga (5–6%), body work (5%), diet-based therapy (4%), progressive relaxation (3%), mega-vitamin therapy (3%) and visualization (2%).
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] In Britain, the most often used alternative therapies were Alexander technique, aromatherapy, Bach and other flower remedies, body work therapies including massage, Counseling stress therapies, hypnotherapy, meditation, reflexology, Shiatsu, Ayurvedic medicine, nutritional medicine, and yoga.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Ayurvedic medicine remedies are mainly plant based with some use of animal materials.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Safety concerns include the use of herbs containing toxic compounds and the lack of quality control in Ayurvedic facilities.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] According to the National Health Service (England), the most commonly used complementary and alternative medicines (CAM) supported by the NHS in the UK are: acupuncture, aromatherapy, chiropractic, homeopathy, massage, osteopathy and clinical hypnotherapy.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Complementary therapies are often used in palliative care or by practitioners attempting to manage chronic pain in patients.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Integrative medicine is considered more acceptable in the interdisciplinary approach used in palliative care than in other areas of medicine.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] "From its early experiences of care for the dying, palliative care took for granted the necessity of placing patient values and lifestyle habits at the core of any design and delivery of quality care at the end of life.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] The alternative medicine lobby has successfully pushed for alternative therapies to be subject to far less regulation than conventional medicine.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Some professions of complementary/traditional/alternative medicine, such as chiropractic, have achieved full regulation in North America and other parts of the world and are regulated in a manner similar to that governing science-based medicine.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] In contrast, other approaches may be partially recognized and others have no regulation at all.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] In some cases, promotion of alternative therapies is allowed when there is demonstrably no effect, only a tradition of use.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Despite laws making it illegal to market or promote alternative therapies for use in cancer treatment, many practitioners promote them.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Regulation and licensing of alternative medicine ranges widely from country to country, and state to state.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] In Austria and Germany complementary and alternative medicine is mainly in the hands of doctors with MDs, and half or more of the American alternative practitioners are licensed MDs.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] In Germany herbs are tightly regulated: half are prescribed by doctors and covered by health insurance.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Government bodies in the US and elsewhere have published information or guidance about alternative medicine.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Food and Drug Administration (FDA), has issued online warnings for consumers about medication health fraud.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] This includes a section on Alternative Medicine Fraud, such as a warning that Ayurvedic products generally have not been approved by the FDA before marketing.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] The National Science Foundation has studied the problematic side of the public's attitudes and understandings of science fiction, pseudoscience, and belief in alternative medicine.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Forms of alternative medicine that are biologically active can be dangerous even when used in conjunction with conventional medicine.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Examples include immuno-augmentation therapy, shark cartilage, bioresonance therapy, oxygen and ozone therapies, and insulin potentiation therapy.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Some herbal remedies can cause dangerous interactions with chemotherapy drugs, radiation therapy, or anesthetics during surgery, among other problems.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Conventional treatments are subjected to testing for undesired side-effects, whereas alternative therapies, in general, are not subjected to such testing at all.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Any treatment – whether conventional or alternative – that has a biological or psychological effect on a patient may also have potential to possess dangerous biological or psychological side-effects.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] An exception to the normal thinking regarding side-effects is homeopathy.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Alternative medicine may discourage people from getting the best possible treatment.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Those having experienced or perceived success with one alternative therapy for a minor ailment may be convinced of its efficacy and persuaded to extrapolate that success to some other alternative therapy for a more serious, possibly life-threatening illness.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] For this reason, critics argue that therapies that rely on the placebo effect to define success are very dangerous.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] According to mental health journalist Scott Lilienfeld in 2002, "unvalidated or scientifically unsupported mental health practices can lead individuals to forgo effective treatments" and refers to this as opportunity cost.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Individuals who spend large amounts of time and money on ineffective treatments may be left with precious little of either, and may forfeit the opportunity to obtain treatments that could be more helpful.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] In short, even innocuous treatments can indirectly produce negative outcomes.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Between 2001 and 2003, four children died in Australia because their parents chose ineffective naturopathic, homeopathic, or other alternative medicines and diets rather than conventional therapies.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] There have always been "many therapies offered outside of conventional cancer treatment centers and based on theories not found in biomedicine.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Complementary and alternative medicine (CAM) is not as well researched as conventional medicine, which undergoes intense research before release to the public.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Practitioners of science-based medicine also discard practices and treatments when they are shown ineffective, while alternative practitioners do not.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Funding for research is also sparse making it difficult to do further research for effectiveness of CAM.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Most funding for CAM is funded by government agencies.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Proposed research for CAM are rejected by most private funding agencies because the results of research are not reliable.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] The research for CAM has to meet certain standards from research ethics committees, which most CAM researchers find almost impossible to meet.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Even with the little research done on it, CAM has not been proven to be effective.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Studies that have been done will be cited by CAM practitioners in an attempt to claim a basis in science.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] These studies tend to have a variety of problems, such as small samples, various biases, poor research design, lack of controls, negative results, etc.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Even those with positive results can be better explained as resulting in false positives due to bias and noisy data.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Alternative medicine may lead to a false understanding of the body and of the process of science.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] It is possible for a method to change categories (proven vs. unproven), based on increased knowledge of its effectiveness or lack thereof.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Prominent supporters of this position are George D.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Lundberg, former editor of the *Journal of the American Medical Association* (*JAMA*) and the journal's interim editor-in-chief Phil Fontanarosa.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Writing in 1999 in *CA: A Cancer Journal for Clinicians* Barrie R.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Cassileth mentioned a 1997 letter to the United States Senate's Subcommittee on Public Health and Safety, which had deplored the lack of critical thinking and scientific rigor in OAM-supported research, had been signed by four Nobel Laureates and other prominent scientists.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Sampson has also pointed out that CAM tolerated contradiction without thorough reason and experiment.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Barrett has pointed out that there is a policy at the NIH of never saying something does not work, only that a different version or dose might give different results.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Barrett also expressed concern that, just because some "alternatives" have merit, there is the impression that the rest deserve equal consideration and respect even though most are worthless, since they are all classified under the one heading of alternative medicine.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Many alternative medical treatments are not patentable, which may lead to less research funding from the private sector.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] In addition, in most countries, alternative therapies (in contrast to pharmaceuticals) can be marketed without any proof of efficacy – also a disincentive for manufacturers to fund scientific research.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] CAM is also often less regulated than conventional medicine.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] There are ethical concerns about whether people who perform CAM have the proper knowledge to treat patients.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] CAM is often done by non-physicians who do not operate with the same medical licensing laws which govern conventional medicine, and it is often described as an issue of non-maleficence.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] According to two writers, Wallace Sampson and K.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Butler, marketing is part of the training required in alternative medicine, and propaganda methods in alternative medicine have been traced back to those used by Hitler and Goebbels in their promotion of pseudoscience in medicine.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] In November 2011 Edzard Ernst stated that the "level of misinformation about alternative medicine has now reached the point where it has become dangerous and unethical.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] So far, alternative medicine has remained an ethics-free zone.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Some commentators have said that special consideration must be given to the issue of conflicts of interest in alternative medicine.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Edzard Ernst has said that most researchers into alternative medicine are at risk of "unidirectional bias" because of a generally uncritical belief in their chosen subject.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Ernst cites as evidence the phenomenon whereby 100% of a sample of acupuncture trials originating in China had positive conclusions.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] David Gorski contrasts evidence-based medicine, in which researchers try to disprove hyphotheses, with what he says is the frequent practice in pseudoscience-based research, of striving to confirm pre-existing notions.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Research into alternative therapies has been criticized for "diverting research time, money, and other resources from more fruitful lines of investigation in order to pursue a theory that has no basis in biology." Research methods expert and author of *Snake Oil Science*, R.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/alternative-medicine-p02] Barker Bausell, has stated that "it's become politically correct to investigate nonsense." A commonly cited statistic is that the US National Institute of Health had spent $2.5 billion on investigating alternative therapies prior to 2009, with none being found to be effective.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/anecdotal-evidence] The term *anecdotal* encompasses a variety of forms of evidence, including personal experiences, self-reported claims, eyewitness accounts of others, and those from fictional sources, making it a broad category that can lead to confusion due to its varied interpretations.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/anecdotal-evidence] Anecdotal evidence can be true or false but is not usually subjected to scholarly methods, scientific methods, or rules of legal, historical, academic, or intellectual rigor, meaning there are little or no safeguards against fabrication or inaccuracy.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/anecdotal-evidence] However, the use of anecdotal reports in advertising or promotion of a product, service, or idea may be considered a testimonial, which is highly regulated in certain jurisdictions.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/anecdotal-evidence] The persuasiveness of anecdotal evidence compared to that of statistical evidence has been a subject of debate; some studies have argued that there is a generalized tendency to overvalue anecdotal evidence, whereas others argue the contrary.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/anecdotal-evidence] Anecdotal evidence may be considered within the scope of scientific methods.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/anecdotal-evidence] Some anecdotal evidence can be both empirical and verifiable, e.g., case studies in medicine.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/anecdotal-evidence] Other anecdotal evidence does not qualify as scientific evidence because its nature prevents it from being investigated by the scientific method, such as folklore or intentionally fictional anecdotes.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/anecdotal-evidence] Anecdotal evidence is considered the least certain type of scientific literature.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/anecdotal-evidence] Researchers may use anecdotal evidence for suggesting new hypotheses but never as validating evidence.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/anecdotal-evidence] For instance, in medicine, published anecdotal evidence by a doctor like a case report is subjected to formal peer review.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/anecdotal-evidence] Although such evidence is seen as inconclusive, researchers sometimes regard it as an invitation to more rigorous scientific study.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/anecdotal-evidence] For instance, one study found that 35 of 47 anecdotal reports of drug side effects were later sustained as "clearly correct".
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/anecdotal-evidence] Where only one or few anecdotes are presented, they risk being unreliable due to cherry-picking or otherwise non-representative sampling.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/anecdotal-evidence] Similarly, psychologists have found that due to cognitive bias, people are more likely to remember notable or unusual examples.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/anecdotal-evidence] Thus, anecdotal evidence is not necessarily representative of a typical experience even when accurate.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/anecdotal-evidence] Determination of whether an anecdote is typical requires statistical evidence.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/anecdotal-evidence] Misuse of anecdotal evidence in the form of **argument from anecdote** is an informal fallacy and is sometimes referred to as the "person who" or **anecdotal fallacy**, with statements like "I know a person who..." or "I know of a case where...".
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/anecdotal-evidence] This places undue weight on possibly atypical experiences of close peers.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/anecdotal-evidence] If an anecdote illustrates a desired conclusion rather than a logical conclusion, it is considered a faulty generalization.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/anecdotal-evidence] In medicine, anecdotal evidence may be subject to the placebo effect.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/anecdotal-evidence] In the legal sphere, anecdotal evidence, if it passes certain legal requirements and is admitted as testimony, is a common form of evidence used in a court of law.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/anecdotal-evidence] In many cases, anecdotal evidence is the only evidence presented at trial.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/anecdotal-evidence] For a testimony to be considered evidence, it must be given under oath, where the individual swears they only testify to their words and actions.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/anecdotal-evidence] Someone intentionally lying under oath is subject to perjury.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/anecdotal-evidence] However, these legal rigors do not make testimony in a court of law equal to scientific evidence.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/anecdotal-evidence] Testimony about another person's experiences or words is termed hearsay and is usually not admissible.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/anecdotal-evidence] However, hearsay that is not objected to by a judge is considered evidence for a jury.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/anecdotal-evidence] This means trials contain a considerable amount of anecdotal evidence that juries find relevant.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/anecdotal-evidence] Eyewitness testimony, a type of anecdotal evidence, is considered the most compelling form of evidence by a jury.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] The specific animal-assisted therapy can be classified by the type of animal, the targeted population, and how the animal is incorporated into the therapeutic plan.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Various animals have been utilized for animal-assisted therapy, with the most common types being canine-assisted therapy and equine-assisted therapy.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Use of these animals in therapies has shown positives results in many cases, such as post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD), depression, anxiety, sexual abuse victims, dementia, and autism.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] It can be used in many different facilities, like hospitals, prisons, and nursing homes, to aid in the therapy provided.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Some studies have shown that animal-assisted therapy can improve many aspects of a patient's life, such as improving their overall mood or reducing feelings of isolation.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Animal-assisted therapy is an alternative or complementary type of therapy that includes the use of animals in a treatment.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] It falls under the realm of animal-assisted intervention, which encompasses any intervention in the studio that includes an animal in a therapeutic context such as emotional support animals, service animals trained to assist with daily activities, and animal-assisted activity.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] The goal of animal-assisted therapy is to improve a patient's social, emotional, or cognitive functioning.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Literature reviews state that animals can be useful for educational and motivational effectiveness for participants.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Animal-assisted therapy can help reduce pain and physiological stress responses, such as a decrease in blood pressure for those who are hospitalized.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] There were studies conducted in both the medical and the palliative care environments that have also shown enhancements in mood, anxiety levels, and overall emotional health.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] These effects have been linked to greater comfort, increased patient engagement, and reduced stress during medical procedures.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Despite overlap, it differs from animal-assisted education, whose focus is teaching and learning with the support of non-human animals.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Research has found that animals can have an overall positive effect on health and improve mood and quality of life.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Studies have documented some positive effects of the therapy on subjective self-rating scales and on objective physiological measures such as blood pressure and hormone levels.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] The positive effect has been linked to the human-animal bond.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] In a variety of settings, such as prisons, nursing homes, and mental institutions, these animals are used to assist people with different disabilities or disorders.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] In modern times animals are seen as "agents of socialization" and as providers of "social support and relaxation".
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] The earliest reported use of the therapy for the mentally ill took place in the late 18th century at the York Retreat in England, led by William Tuke.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Patients at this facility were allowed to wander the grounds which contained a population of small domestic animals.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] These were believed to be effective tools for socialization.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] In 1860, the Bethlem Hospital in England followed the same trend and added animals to the ward, greatly influencing the morale of the patients living there.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Other literature refers to animal-assisted therapy being used as early as 1792 at the Quaker Society of Friends York Retreat in England.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] The US military promoted the use of dogs as a therapeutic intervention with psychiatric patients in 1919 at St Elizabeth's Hospital in Washington, DC.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Sigmund Freud kept many dogs and often had his chow Jofi present during his pioneering sessions of psychoanalysis.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] He noticed that the presence of the dog was helpful because the patient would find that their speech would not shock or disturb the dog and this reassured them and so encouraged them to relax and confide.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] This was most effective when the patient was a child or adolescent.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Increased recognition of the value of human–pet bonding was noted by Dr.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Levinson accidentally used animals in therapy with children when he left his dog alone with a nonverbal child, and upon returning, found the child talking to the dog.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Wilson's (1984) biophilia hypothesis is based on the premise that our attachment to and interest in animals stems from the strong possibility that human survival was partly dependent on signals from animals in the environment indicating safety or threat.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] The biophilia hypothesis suggests that if we see animals at rest or in a peaceful state, this may signal to us safety, security and feelings of well-being which in turn may trigger a state where personal change and healing are possible.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Six neurotransmitters that influence mood have been documented to release after a 15-minute or more interaction with animals.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Mirror neuron activity and disease-perception through olfactory (smelling) ability in dogs may also play important roles in helping dogs connect with humans during therapeutic encounters.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Animal-assisted therapy has also been shown to have a positive impact on brain, neurochemical, and cardiovascular function.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Interventions involving canines has been shown to decrease blood pressure, the stress hormones epinephrine and norepinephrine, and increase hormones associated with pleasure, like dopamine and oxytocin.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Animals can be integrated into settings such as prisons, nursing homes, mental institutions, and in the home.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] The techniques used depend on the needs and condition of the patient.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Assistance dogs can support certain life activities and help people navigate outside the home.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Assessing whether a program is effective as far as its outcomes are concerned is easier when the goals are clear and are able to be specified.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] There are a range of goals for animal-assisted therapy programs relevant to children and young people, including enhanced capacity to form positive relationships with others.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] It is understood that pets provide benefits to those with mental health conditions, but further research is required to test the nature and extent of this relationship with an animal as a pet and how it differs between pets, emotional support animals, service animals, and animal-assisted therapy.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Acquired brain injury survivors with cognitive impairments can benefit from animal-assisted therapy as part of a comprehensive rehabilitation treatment plan.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Animals can be used as a distraction method when it comes to various situations or pain, and animals can also help bring happiness, pleasure, and entertainment to the pediatric population.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Animals can also help improve children's moods and reinforce positive behaviors while helping to decrease negative ones.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Therapists rely on techniques such as monitoring a child's behavior with the animal, their tone of voice, and indirect interviewing.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Animal-assisted therapy can be used in children with mental health problems, as a stand-alone treatment, or along with conventional methods.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Animal-assisted therapy (AAT) is used in hospital settings with children to try to improve their overall well-being and mood during their stay.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Most commonly reported research results are decreased anxiety and pain within the pediatric population.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] One area of pediatric hospital care in which the use of AAT has been studied is magnetic resonance imaging procedures which can trigger negative emotions in children, causing them to move and require procedural sedation.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] After AAT intervention, the anxiety levels of the subjects decreased significantly when compared to controls.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Dogs have been shown to increase comfort and decrease pain in pediatric palliative care.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Specific tactics have not been researched, but collective reviews of varied techniques displayed similar results of increased comfort reports by children and guardians.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Though meta-analysis has determined that children receiving AAT have seen a reduction in pain when compared to control groups, further quantitative research is needed to confirm this conclusion.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Though AAT has existed and been in practice for decades, the lack of standardization creates potential risks for both the animals and humans involved.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] As the use among pediatric populations continues to climb, another concern that has been raised about the use of animals in a hospital setting is the spread of germs.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Many children in hospital settings have weakened immune systems and are already at risk of contracting hospital-borne infections.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] It has been found that both the patients and dogs participating in therapy experienced changes to their biome after their sessions.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Whether these changes pose a long-term benefit or risk has yet to be proven, and more in-depth studies are needed to make this determination.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Additionally researchers are working to find an accurate way to determine the effects of AAT on both the service animal and the human participating in therapy.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Animal-assistance programs, such as cell dog programs, may be useful in prisons to relieve stress of the inmates and workers, or to provide other benefits, but further study is needed to confirm the effectiveness of such programs in these settings.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Internal file data reviews, anecdotal stories, and surveys of inmate and staff perceptions have been used to gauge the effectiveness of animal-assisted therapy in prisons, but these methods are limited and have resulted in an inadequate assessment.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Researchers have, however, begun to find methods of gauging the effectiveness of prison animal programs (PAPs) by using Propensity Score Watching.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] One study using this method found that PAPs positively impact reductions in severe or violent infractions.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] A reduction in offenses statistically may reduce recidivism rates and increase former inmate job marketability and societal reintegration.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Training and being responsible for an animal can foster empathy, emotional intelligence, communication, and self-control in inmates; however, the results of studies done so far must be taken with caution as the methodological quality of existing studies is limited.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] PAPs also benefit the animals involved as many come from situations where they faced abuse, neglect or potential euthanasia.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] The findings offer proof of the concept that canine-assisted therapies are feasible and can elicit positive quality-of-life experiences in institutionalized people with dementia.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Researchers and practitioners need to elucidate the theoretical foundations of animal-assisted therapies.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] The Lived Environment Life Quality Model may serve as a guide for client-centered, occupation-focused, and ecologically valid approaches to animal-assisted occupational therapy beyond people with dementia.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] When elderly people are transferred to nursing homes or long-term care facilities, they often become passive, agitated, withdrawn, depressed, and inactive because of the lack of regular visitors or the loss of loved ones.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Supporters of animal-assisted therapy say that animals can be helpful in motivating the patients to be active mentally and physically, keeping their minds sharp and bodies healthy.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] A significant difference has been seen among verbal interactions among nursing home residents with a dog present.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Therapists or visitors who bring animals into their sessions at the nursing home are often viewed as less threatening, which increases the relationship between the therapist or visitor and patient.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Occupational therapists can use animal-assisted therapies to work on the child's motivation.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Some occupational therapy goals using animal-assisted therapies include improving attention skills, social skills, participation in play, self-esteem, and reducing anxiety, loneliness, and isolation.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Various animal species are used in animal-assisted therapy.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Individual animals are evaluated with strict criteria before being used.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] The criteria include appropriate size, age, aptitude, typical behaviors and the correct level of training.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] The most commonly used species are dogs and horses.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Research has been published on dolphin therapy.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] In canine-assisted therapy, therapy dogs interact with patients in animal assisted interventions, to enhance therapeutic activities and well-being including the physical, cognitive, behavioral and socio-emotional functioning of clients.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Well-trained therapy dogs exhibit the behavior that human patients construe as friendly and welcoming.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Therapy dogs are also required to possess a calm temperament for accommodating the contact with unfamiliar clients while they serve as a source of comfort.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] They promote patients engaging in interactions which can help patient improve motor skills and establish trusting relationship with others.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] The interaction between patients and therapy dogs also aids reducing stressful and anxious feelings patients have.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Due to those benefits, canine-assisted therapy is used as a complement to other therapies to treat diagnosis such as post-traumatic stress disorder, attention deficit hyperactivity disorder, autism spectrum disorder, and dementia.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Canine assistance can also be used in classroom for promoting the development of creative writing and living skills and the participation of children in group activities.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] There are programs called canine-assisted reading programs which facilitate children with special educational needs.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] These programs utilize the calm, non-judgmental, happy characteristics of canines to let the process of reading become more meaningful and enjoyable for children.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] With these benefits, researchers suggest incorporating dogs into assisting learning and educational programs.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Dolphin-assisted therapy refers to the controversial alternative medicine practice of swimming with dolphins.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] This form of therapy has been strongly criticized as having no long-term benefit, and being based on flawed observations.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Psychologists have cautioned that dolphin-assisted therapy is not known to be effective for any condition and that it presents considerable risks to both human patients and the captive dolphins.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] The child has a one-on-one session with a therapist in a marine park.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] An ethical issue with data on dolphin-assisted therapy and the effectiveness of it is that most of the research is done by people who operate the dolphin-assisted therapy programs.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Equine-assisted therapy encompasses a range of treatments that involve activities with horses and other equines to promote human physical and mental health.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Therapeutic riding is used by disabled individuals who ride horses to relax, and to develop muscle tone, coordination, confidence, and well-being.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Equine-assisted psychotherapy (EAP) or Equine Facilitated Psychotherapy (EFP) is the use of equines to treat human psychological problems in and around an equestrian facility.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] The existing body of evidence does not justify the promotion and use of equine-related treatments for mental disorders.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Pigs have been used in various types of animal-assisted therapy to perform duties in facilities including airports, hospitals, nursing homes, and special-needs schools, or as emotional support animals for individuals with conditions such as autism or anxiety and veterans with PTSD.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Two well-known miniature pigs named Thunder and Bolt trained by children to certified animal therapy status have been put to work in a number of nursing homes, schools and a hospital.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] For patients that have allergies to animals that have fur, snakes have been used to provide emotional support.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Based on current research, there are many conditions that can benefit from animal-assisted therapy in diverse settings around the world.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Those conditions include psychological disorder, developmental disorder, dementia, chronic pain, advanced heart failure, etc.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Animal-assisted therapy is commonly used for psychological disorders.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder, autism spectrum disorder, post-traumatic stress disorder, and major depressive disorder are among the psychological disorders that can benefit from animal-assisted therapy.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] In recent decades, an increased amount of research indicates the social, psychological, and physiological benefits of animal-assisted therapy in the fields of health and education.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] In addition to its typical application in clinical disorders, recent research has focused on studying animal-assisted therapy in broader populations.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] A 2025 meta-analysis of randomized controlled trials determined that interactions with therapy dogs were associated with notable reductions in anxiety and stress levels among college students.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] The most significant improvements were reported by students who began with higher stress levels, indicating that these interventions could be specifically useful for individuals experiencing elevated psychological strain.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Similar results have been observed in other contexts, including among otherwise healthy healthcare workers participating in animal-assisted programs.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] While additional research is necessary, current outcomes suggest that animal-assisted therapy could provide a viable option for reducing anxiety and stress and supporting the emotional health of young adult populations.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Research on animal-assisted therapy within inpatient and psychiatric health settings has shown potential benefits for youth.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] A recent systematic review of animal-assisted therapy for adolescents and children found enhanced social behavior, improved mood, and reduced anxiety levels after structured interactions with therapy dogs.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Participants demonstrated greater willingness to take part in therapeutic activities and showed more consistent emotional responsiveness during treatment.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] These findings suggested that animal-assisted therapy might support the therapeutic processes in inpatient environments by encouraging participation and lowering emotional distress.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] The review noted that, despite the outcomes reflecting significant improvements, the applicability of findings might be limited by small sample sizes and variability in intervention structure across studies.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] The feasibility of integrating therapy dogs into inpatient treatment for children has recently been examined.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] This study involved children with acquired brain injury and their families and aimed to determine whether the presence of therapy dogs would be accepted in an inpatient rehabilitation setting.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] The outcome suggested that the integration of therapy dogs was positively accepted by the patients, their families, and the clinical staff, and the dogs did not interfere with standard rehabilitation practices.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] The patients reported increased enjoyment and motivation during treatment, which supports genuine engagement within inpatient settings.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] These findings complement earlier studies indicating that therapy dogs can support social interaction, emotional regulation, and participation among children and adolescents receiving mental healthcare in inpatient settings.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] The culmination of this research specifies the potential for animal-assisted therapy to positively impact rehabilitative and psychological outcomes for children in multiple inpatient care contexts.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Animal-assisted therapy (AAT) is also used in the oncology and the palliative care settings to support patients coping with cancer and advanced illnesses.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Some systematic reviews have reported improvements in patients emotional well-being, including reductions in anxiety and distress, after they interact with the therapy animals during treatment or hospitalization.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Animal-assisted interventions (AAI) in palliative care may help lessen the feelings of loneliness, promote comfort, and encourage crucial social interaction with family and/or friends for patients who are facing the common physical and emotional burdens that come along with cancer care.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Research also notes a decrease in pain and physiological stress responses, like lower blood pressure in some patient groups, which could contribute to an increased feeling of relaxation during medical procedures.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Using these findings, we can see that animal-assisted therapy is able to positively complement medical and psychosocial care by providing the emotional support patients need as well as improve their comfortability in and out of the clinical settings.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Children with attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) may decrease behavioral issues and improve socialization skills with the intervention of animal-assisted therapy.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Compared to children who received only cognitive-behavioral therapy, children who received both canine-assisted therapy and cognitive-behavioral therapy had reduced severity of ADHD symptoms.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] However, the dog-assisted therapy did not relieve symptoms in long-term treatment.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD) is a psychological disorder affects people's mental health and has varying severity and forms.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] It is often difficult to treat due to high drop-out rates and low responses to traditional psycho-therapeutic approaches and interventions.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Animals have both direct and indirect effects on a mental health spectrum including biological, psychological, and social responses, further targeting marked symptoms of post-traumatic stress disorder (i.e., re-experiencing, avoidance, changes in beliefs/feelings, and hyperarousal).
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Direct effects of animals include a decrease in anxiety and blood pressure while indirect effects result in increased social interactions and overall participation in everyday activities.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Biologically, specific chemicals are released when observing human and animal interactions.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Similarly, dog assistance can potentially mediate oxytocin which effects social and physical well-being and decrease blood pressure.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] The psychological benefits of animals focus mainly on dog and human interactions, the reduction of anxiety and depressive symptoms, and increased resilience.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Animals in this capacity can further provide emotional and psychological assistance and support, addressing several of the disorder's symptoms.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] The presence of an animal can alleviate intrusion symptoms by providing a reminder that there is no danger present.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Animals can further elicit positive emotions, targeting emotional numbing experiences.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Animal interactions also provide social benefits, providing companionship and alleviate feelings of loneliness and isolation through everyday routines and increased social interactions in public.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] The incorporation and involvement of animals dates back to the earliest forms of organized combat.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Dogs, in particular, were utilized in different capacities.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Ancient armies employed dogs as soldiers and companions which extended to modern combat including dogs as a crucial asset in communication, detection, and intimidation.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] While a range of animals can be utilized, dogs and horses have been the principal species studied in practice.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Dog-assisted therapy and therapeutic horseback riding are non-invasive methods for treating post-traumatic stress disorder in veterans.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Canines can easily integrate into a multitude of environments, are highly responsive to humans, and are very intelligent.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] For those reasons, dogs are the species most commonly used in interventions.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Dogs are typically categorized according to the level of training received and the specific needs of the individual.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] A service dog provides relief through specialized support related to a physical, mental, or psychological disability.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Emotional support animals solely provide psychological relief and do not require specialized training.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Therapy animals often provide additional support in a therapeutic environment by supporting counselors or therapists in their therapeutic duties.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Dogs provide subjective positive effects to veterans and serve as a compassionate reminder to veterans with post-traumatic stress disorder that danger is not present, creating a safe space for the veteran.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] They are often sensitive to humans and have the ability to adapt their behavior accordingly by doing tasks such as preventing panic, waking a veteran from a nightmare, and nudging to help the veteran "stay in the present".
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Dogs provide veterans with a nonjudgmental and safe environment that can help a veteran express feelings and process thoughts without interruption, criticism or advice.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Interactions, such as petting, playing and walking, with the dog can increase physical activity, reduce anxiety, and provide encouragement to stay in the present moment.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] The interaction between dog and veterans supports social interactions for isolated veterans, reduces symptoms associated with the disorder such as depression and anxiety, and increases veterans' calmness.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Similar to dogs, horses have been included in the treatment of veterans with post-traumatic stress disorder by providing an accepting and nonjudgmental environment, which further facilitates a veterans' ability to cope with symptoms.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Because horses are social animals, they are capable of creating and responding to relationships based on the veteran's energy, providing an opportunity for veterans to regain the ability to form trusting relationships.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Therapeutic work with horses varies from ground-based activities, mounted activities, or a combination of both.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] In the therapeutic context, horses can promote cognitive reframing as well as an increase in the use of mindfulness practice.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] While there is limited research and standardized instruments to measure the effects, veterans who have participated in pilot programs have better communication skills, self-awareness, and self-esteem, promoting safety and support during the transition into civilian life.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Long-term effects of equine-based interventions with veterans include increased happiness, social support, and better sleep hygiene because they are able to process information regarding their emotions and behaviors in a nonjudgmental space.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] While animal-assisted interventions may be effective, it is not yet verified due to limited research.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Animal-assisted interventions can be challenging to study.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Because of lack of effective resources, most studies are limited to small sample sizes which prevents generalizing results over a larger population.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Furthermore, there is often a lack of randomization and a lack of information about sample representativeness that prevents widespread application.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Hospital-based animal-assisted therapy programs may present a slight risk of pathogen transmission, but further research is needed.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] The disorder can develop when a person experiences a sexual assault or rape.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Sexual assault is the leading cause of post-traumatic stress disorder in women; an estimated 50% of women who were sexually assaulted develop the condition.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Animal-assisted therapy can be an effective in treating the trauma for survivors of sexual assault.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] The presence of dogs have been shown to improve communication between the survivor and the therapist and to decrease survivors' anxiety and fear-responses.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Animal-assisted therapy increases social interaction for those with the disorder.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Studies show that animal-assisted therapy leads to an overall reduction of symptoms including anger, depression, and dissociation in survivors of sexual assault.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Animal-assisted therapy has also been shown to reduce problem behavior and improves overall behavioral functioning for children survivors of sexual assault.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Further research is needed to show the effectiveness of animal-assisted interventions in treating post-traumatic stress disorder for sexual assault survivors across varying demographics.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Limitations in current research include small sample sizes and reliance on anecdotal evidence.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Animal-assisted therapy may reduce the symptoms of autism spectrum disorder such as aggressiveness, irritability, difficulty concentrating, and hyperactivity.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] In one review, five out of nine studies reviewed showed positive effects of therapeutic horseback riding on children with autism spectrum disorder.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Canine-assisted intervention provides a calmer environment by reducing the stress, irritation, and anxiety that children with autism spectrum disorder experience.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Playing with dogs increases positive mood in children with autism spectrum disorder.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Animals also can serve as a social catalyst.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] In the presence of animals, children with autism spectrum disorder are more likely to engage in social interactions with humans.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] However, the impact of animal-assisted therapy upon parent–child interaction is not clear.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Animal-assisted therapy encourages expressions of emotions and cognitive stimulation through discussions and reminiscing of memories while the patient bonds with the animal.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Studies have found that animal-assisted therapies (particularly using dogs) resulted in measurable quality of life improvements for patients with dementia.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Patients with dementia were also found to improve their social interactions and their scores on the Cohen-Mansfield Agitation Inventory.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Animal-assisted therapy has been shown to slightly reduce depressive symptoms in people with dementia in a 2019 systematic review.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Another systematic review and meta-analysis related to animal-assisted therapy in older adults experiencing dementia and Alzheimer's disease was recently conducted.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] This analysis found that structured interactions with therapy animals were associated with improvements in mood, communication, and engagement during therapeutic practices.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Participants displayed increased responsiveness and reduced emotional distress, which can support emotional stability and social interaction in this geriatric population.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] While these findings indicate positive benefits, the review noted that the outcomes might be limited by smaller sample sizes and variable intervention methods across studies.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] The benefits of animal-assisted therapy could be related to its ability to provide emotional support and reduce stress reactions.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] A systematic review of canine-assisted therapy for college students determined that the interactions with therapy dogs were associated with lower stress and anxiety levels.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] These interactions have been reported to help individuals feel more calm and supported, which could strengthen their ability and willingness to engage in therapeutic practices.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Equine-assisted therapies for people with autism spectrum disorder have also been connected to improvements in regulation of emotions and social communication, which suggests that structured interactions with animals can have positive impacts on behavioral control and social engagement.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] This research suggests that animal-assisted therapy can influence social and emotional functioning, which contributes to a greater sense of comfortability and deeper engagement during treatment.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] There is limited scientific research on the use of the therapy among adults who have been sexually assaulted.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] While animals do tend to comfort survivors, animal therapy may not be the catalyst that provides positive success in therapy sessions.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] As mentioned above, adults tend not to focus as much on having an animal companion, and therefore, animal therapy cannot be attributed as the reason for success in those types of therapy sessions.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] There are some ethical concerns that arise when applying animal therapy to younger survivors of sexual assault.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] For example, if a child is introduced to an animal that is not their pet, the application of animal therapy can cause some concerns.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] First of all, some children may not be comfortable with animals or may be frightened which could be avoided by asking permission to use animals in therapy.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Second, a special bond is created between animal and child during animal therapy.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Therefore, if the animal in question does not belong to the child, there may be some negative side effects when the child discontinues therapy.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] The child will have become attached to the animal, which does raise some ethical issues as far as subjecting a child to the disappointment and possible relapse that can occur after therapy discontinues.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] It is unclear to what degree the animal itself contributes in the recovery process.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] There are some concerns specific to dolphin-assisted therapy: First, it is potentially hazardous to the human patients, and it is harmful to the dolphins themselves; by taking dolphins out of their natural environment and putting them in captivity for therapy can be hazardous to their well-being.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Second, dolphin-assisted therapy has been strongly criticized as having no long-term benefit, and being based on flawed observations.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Third, psychologists have cautioned that dolphin-assisted therapy is not effective for any known condition.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] There are concerns that people may become dependent on the animal and could interfere with the recovery process for PTSD.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] People may feel as though they cannot do things on their own without the presence of the animal.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Due to the unclear structural guidelines on the use of animals in therapeutic settings, possible impacts to the animal include stress, injury, and health complications.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Research has shown that despite quality guidelines in place to ensure the health of the therapy animal, there are reports of negative interactions between human participant and therapy dogs.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] These reports include mistreating and teasing the dogs by patients and staff at locations in which therapy is hosted.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] In studies conducted, people with certain disabilities had to be excluded from the experiment due to increase in the stress of the therapy dog, and ultimately decline in overall well-being.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] There is a question as to whether bringing animals into AAT settings where the client has a history of violence is ethical, or if the benefit outweighs the risk.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Equine-assisted therapy showed a need for more studies of equine behavior to obtain an understanding of stress signals from horses.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Through understanding the stress signals shown by horses, a safe and healthy experience during the therapy session can be held, by allowing handlers to minimize stress.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] For therapy animals limited time for rest, multiple sessions, and long duration of sessions were linked to higher stress.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Assessing animals for signs of fatigue and stress can prevent negative experience for both humans and animals involved.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Animals used should be limited to a specific duration and number of sessions, as well as given access to proper environmental conditions, food, water, and rest.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Ethical analysis extends beyond stress during sessions to the broader commodification and breeding of animals for therapeutic roles.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-assisted-therapy] Critics point to practices like breeding dogs for specific "looks" conducive to therapy without regard for genetic health problems, or the early separation and intensive training of service dogs, as systemic issues that prioritize human utility over animal integrity.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] The mind and behavior of non-human animals has captivated the human imagination for centuries.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] Many writers, such as Descartes, have speculated about the presence or absence of the animal mind.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] These speculations led to many observations of animal behavior before modern science and testing were available.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] This ultimately resulted in the creation of multiple hypotheses about animal intelligence.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] One of Aesop's Fables was *The Crow and the Pitcher*, in which a crow drops pebbles into a vessel of water until he is able to drink.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] This was a relatively accurate reflection of the capability of corvids to understand water displacement.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] The Roman naturalist Pliny the Elder was the earliest to attest that said story reflects the behavior of real-life corvids.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] Aristotle, in his biology, hypothesized a causal chain where an animal's sense organs transmitted information to an organ capable of making decisions, and then to a motor organ.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] Despite Aristotle's cardiocentrism (mistaken belief that cognition occurred in the heart), this approached some modern understandings of information processing.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] Early inferences were not necessarily precise or accurate.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] Nonetheless, interest in animal mental abilities, and comparisons to humans, increased with early myrmecology, the study of ant behavior, as well as the classification of humans as primates beginning with Linnaeus.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] Coined by 19th-century British psychologist C.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] Lloyd Morgan, Morgan's Canon remains a fundamental precept of comparative (animal) psychology.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] Speculation about animal intelligence gradually yielded to scientific study after Darwin placed humans and animals on a continuum, although Darwin's largely anecdotal approach to the cognition topic would not pass scientific muster later on.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] This method would be expanded by his protégé George J.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] Romanes, who played a key role in the defense of Darwinism and its refinement over the years.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] Still, Romanes is most famous for two major flaws in his work: his focus on anecdotal observations and entrenched anthropomorphism.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] Unsatisfied with the previous approach, E.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] Thorndike brought animal behavior into the laboratory for objective scrutiny.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] Thorndike's careful observations of the escape of cats, dogs, and chicks from puzzle boxes led him to conclude that what appears to the naive human observer to be intelligent behavior may be strictly attributable to simple associations.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] According to Thorndike, using Morgan's Canon, the inference of animal reason, insight, or consciousness is unnecessary and misleading.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] Pavlov began his seminal studies of conditioned reflexes in dogs.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] Pavlov quickly abandoned attempts to infer canine mental processes; such attempts, he said, led only to disagreement and confusion.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] He was, however, willing to propose unseen physiological processes that might explain his observations.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] The work of Thorndike, Pavlov and a little later of the outspoken behaviorist John B.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] Watson set the direction of much research on animal behavior for more than half a century.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] During this time there was considerable progress in understanding simple associations; notably, around 1930 the differences between Thorndike's instrumental (or operant) conditioning and Pavlov's classical (or Pavlovian) conditioning were clarified, first by Miller and Kanorski, and then by B.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] Many experiments on conditioning followed; they generated some complex theories, but they made little or no reference to intervening mental processes.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] Probably the most explicit dismissal of the idea that mental processes control behavior was the radical behaviorism of Skinner.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] This view seeks to explain behavior, including "private events" like mental images, solely by reference to the environmental contingencies impinging on the human or animal.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] Despite the predominantly behaviorist orientation of research before 1960, the rejection of mental processes in animals was not universal during those years.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] Influential exceptions included, for example, Wolfgang Köhler and his insightful chimpanzees and Edward Tolman whose proposed cognitive map was a significant contribution to subsequent cognitive research in both humans and animals.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] Beginning around 1960, a "cognitive revolution" in research on humans gradually spurred a similar transformation of research with animals.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] Inference to processes not directly observable became acceptable and then commonplace.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] An important proponent of this shift in thinking was Donald O.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] Hebb, who argued that "mind" is simply a name for processes in the head that control complex behavior, and that it is both necessary and possible to infer those processes from behavior.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] Animals came to be seen as "goal seeking agents that acquire, store, retrieve, and internally process information at many levels of cognitive complexity".
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] The acceleration of research on animal cognition in the last 50 years or so has led to a rapid expansion in the variety of species studied and methods employed.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] The remarkable behavior of large-brained animals such as primates and cetacea have claimed special attention, but all sorts of animals large and small (birds, fish, ants, bees, and others) have been brought into the laboratory or observed in carefully controlled field studies.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] In the laboratory, animals push levers, pull strings, dig for food, swim in water mazes, or respond to images on computer screens to get information for discrimination, attention, memory, and categorization experiments.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] Careful field studies explore memory for food caches, navigation by stars, communication, tool use, identification of conspecifics, and many other matters.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] Studies often focus on the behavior of animals in their natural environments and discuss the putative function of the behavior for the propagation and survival of the species.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] These developments reflect an increased cross-fertilization from related fields such as ethology and behavioral ecology.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] Contributions from behavioral neuroscience are beginning to clarify the physiological substrate of some inferred mental process.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] Some researchers have made effective use of a Piagetian methodology, taking tasks which human children are known to master at different stages of development and investigating which of them can be performed by particular species.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] Others have been inspired by concerns for animal welfare and the management of domestic species; for example, Temple Grandin has harnessed her unique expertise in animal welfare and the ethical treatment of farm livestock to highlight underlying similarities between humans and other animals.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p01] From a methodological point of view, one of the main risks in this sort of work is anthropomorphism, the tendency to interpret an animal's behavior in terms of human feelings, thoughts, and motivations.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Human and non-human animal cognition have much in common, and this is reflected in the research summarized below; most of the headings found here might also appear in an article on human cognition.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Of course, research in the two also differs in important respects.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Notably, much research with humans either studies or involves language, and much research with animals is related directly or indirectly to behaviors important to survival in natural settings.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Following are summaries of some of the major areas of research in animal cognition.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Evolutionary approaches to animal cognition have emphasized that learning and other cognitive abilities are shaped by the structure of environmental change.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The predictability and timescale of ecological variation are considered key determinants of when learning should evolve, and recent syntheses have highlighted the need for standardized measures of environmental change to better connect theoretical models with empirical systems.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Animals process information from eyes, ears, and other sensory organs to perceive the environment.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Perceptual processes have been studied in many species, with results that are often similar to those in humans.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Equally interesting are those perceptual processes that differ from, or go beyond those found in humans, such as echolocation in bats and dolphins, motion detection by skin receptors in fish, and extraordinary visual acuity, motion sensitivity and ability to see ultraviolet light in some birds.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Much of what is happening in the world at any moment is irrelevant to current behavior.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Attention refers to mental processes that select relevant information, inhibit irrelevant information, and switch among these as the situation demands.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Often the selective process is tuned before relevant information appears; such expectation makes for rapid selection of key stimuli when they become available.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] A large body of research has explored the way attention and expectation affect the behavior of non-human animals, and much of this work suggests that attention operates in birds, mammals and reptiles in much the same way that it does in humans.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Animals trained to discriminate between two stimuli, such as black versus white, can be said to attend to the "brightness dimension", but this says little about whether this dimension is selected in preference to others.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] More enlightenment comes from experiments that allow the animal to choose from several alternatives.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] For example, several studies have shown that performance is better on, for example, a color discrimination (e.g. blue vs green) after the animal has learned another color discrimination (e.g. red vs orange) than it is after training on a different dimension such as an X shape versus an O shape.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The reverse effect happens after training on forms.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Thus, the earlier learning appears to affect which dimension, color or form, the animal will attend to.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Other experiments have shown that after animals have learned to respond to one aspect of the environment responsiveness to other aspects is suppressed.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] In "blocking", for example, an animal is conditioned to respond to one stimulus ("A") by pairing that stimulus with reward or punishment.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] After the animal responds consistently to A, a second stimulus ("B") accompanies A on additional training trials.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Later tests with the B stimulus alone elicit little response, suggesting that learning about B has been blocked by prior learning about A.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] This result supports the hypothesis that stimuli are neglected if they fail to provide new information.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Thus, in the experiment just cited, the animal failed to attend to B because B added no information to that supplied by A.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] If true, this interpretation is an important insight into attentional processing, but this conclusion remains uncertain because blocking and several related phenomena can be explained by models of conditioning that do not invoke attention.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Attention is a limited resource and is not a none-or-all response: the more attention devoted to one aspect of the environment, the less is available for others.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] A number of experiments have studied this in animals.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] In one experiment, a tone and a light are presented simultaneously to pigeons.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The pigeons gain a reward only by choosing the correct combination of the two stimuli (e.g. a high frequency tone together with a yellow light).
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The birds perform well at this task, presumably by dividing attention between the two stimuli.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] When only one of the stimuli varies and the other is presented at its rewarded value, discrimination improves on the variable stimulus but discrimination on the alternative stimulus worsens.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] These outcomes are consistent with the notion that attention is a limited resource that can be more or less focused among incoming stimuli.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] As noted above, the function of attention is to select information that is of special use to the animal.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Visual search typically calls for this sort of selection, and search tasks have been used extensively in both humans and animals to determine the characteristics of attentional selection and the factors that control it.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Experimental research on visual search in animals was initially prompted by field observations published by Luc Tinbergen (1960).
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Tinbergen observed that birds are selective when foraging for insects.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] For example, he found that birds tended to catch the same type of insect repeatedly even though several types were available.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Tinbergen suggested that this prey selection was caused by an attentional bias that improved detection of one type of insect while suppressing detection of others.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] This "attentional priming" is commonly said to result from a pretrial activation of a mental representation of the attended object, which Tinbergen called a "searching image".
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Tinbergen's field observations on priming have been supported by a number of experiments.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] For example, Pietrewicz and Kamil (1977, 1979) presented blue jays with pictures of tree trunks upon which rested either a moth of species A, a moth of species B, or no moth at all.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The birds were rewarded for pecks at a picture showing a moth.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Crucially, the probability with which a particular species of moth was detected was higher after repeated trials with that species (e.g.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] A, A, A,...) than it was after a mixture of trials (e.g.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] These results suggest again that sequential encounters with an object can establish an attentional predisposition to see the object.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Another way to produce attentional priming in search is to provide an advance signal that is associated with the target.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] For example, if a person hears a song sparrow he or she may be predisposed to detect a song sparrow in a shrub, or among other birds.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] A number of experiments have reproduced this effect in animal subjects.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Still other experiments have explored nature of stimulus factors that affect the speed and accuracy of visual search.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] For example, the time taken to find a single target increases as the number of items in the visual field increases.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] This rise in reaction time is steep if the distracters are similar to the target, less steep if they are dissimilar, and may not occur if the distracters are very different from the target in form or color.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Fundamental but difficult to define, the concept of "concept" was discussed for hundreds of years by philosophers before it became a focus of psychological study.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Concepts enable humans and animals to organize the world into functional groups; the groups may be composed of perceptually similar objects or events, diverse things that have a common function, relationships such as same versus different, or relations among relations such as analogies.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Most work on animal concepts has been done with visual stimuli, which can easily be constructed and presented in great variety, but auditory and other stimuli have been used as well.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Pigeons have been widely used, for they have excellent vision and are readily conditioned to respond to visual targets; other birds and a number of other animals have been studied as well.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] In a typical experiment, a bird or other animal confronts a computer monitor on which a large number of pictures appear one by one, and the subject gets a reward for pecking or touching a picture of a category item and no reward for non-category items.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Alternatively, a subject may be offered a choice between two or more pictures.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Many experiments end with the presentation of items never seen before; successful sorting of these items shows that the animal has not simply learned many specific stimulus-response associations.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] A related method, sometimes used to study relational concepts, is matching-to-sample.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] In this task an animal sees one stimulus and then chooses between two or more alternatives, one of which is the same as the first; the animal is then rewarded for choosing the matching stimulus.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Perceptual categorization is said to occur when a person or animal responds in a similar way to a range of stimuli that share common features.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] For example, a squirrel climbs a tree when it sees Rex, Shep, or Trixie, which suggests that it categorizes all three as something to avoid.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] This sorting of instances into groups is crucial to survival.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Among other things, an animal must categorize if it is to apply learning about one object (e.g.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Rex bit me) to new instances of that category (dogs may bite).
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Many animals readily classify objects by perceived differences in form or color.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] For example, bees or pigeons quickly learn to choose any red object and reject any green object if red leads to reward and green does not.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] A more demanding task, at least in principle, is categorizing natural objects that vary widely in color and form even while belonging to the same group.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Herrnstein trained pigeons to respond to the presence or absence of human beings in photographs.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The birds readily learned to peck photos that contained partial or full views of humans and to avoid pecking photos with no human, despite great differences in the form, size, and color of both the humans displayed and in the non-human pictures.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] In follow-up studies, pigeons categorized other natural objects (e.g. trees) and after training they were able without reward to sort photos they had not seen before.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Similar work has been done with natural auditory categories, for example, bird songs.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Honeybees (*Apis mellifera*) are able to form concepts of "up" and "down".
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Perceptually unrelated stimuli may come to be responded to as members of a class if they have a common use or lead to common consequences.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] An oft-cited study by Vaughan (1988) provides an example.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Vaughan divided a large set of unrelated pictures into two arbitrary sets, A and B.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Pigeons got food for pecking at pictures in set A but not for pecks at pictures in set B.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] After they had learned this task fairly well, the outcome was reversed: items in set B led to food and items in set A did not.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Then the outcome was reversed again, and then again, and so on.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Several other procedures have yielded similar results.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Better evidence is provided if, after training, an animal successfully makes a choice that matches a novel sample that it has never seen before.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Monkeys and chimpanzees do learn to do this, as do pigeons if they are given a great deal of practice with many different stimuli.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] However, because the sample is presented first, successful matching might mean that the animal is simply choosing the most recently seen "familiar" item rather than the conceptually "same" item.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] A number of studies have attempted to distinguish these possibilities, with mixed results.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The use of rules has sometimes been considered an ability restricted to humans, but a number of experiments have shown evidence of simple rule learning in primates and also in other animals.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Much of the evidence has come from studies of sequence learning in which the "rule" consists of the order in which a series of events occurs.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Rule use is shown if the animal learns to discriminate different orders of events and transfers this discrimination to new events arranged in the same order.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] For example, Murphy *et al.* (2008) trained rats to discriminate between visual sequences.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] For one group ABA and BAB were rewarded, where A="bright light" and B="dim light".
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Other stimulus triplets were not rewarded.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The rats learned the visual sequence, although both bright and dim lights were equally associated with reward.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] More importantly, in a second experiment with auditory stimuli, rats responded correctly to sequences of novel stimuli that were arranged in the same order as those previously learned.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Similar sequence learning has been demonstrated in birds and other animals as well.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Memory has been widely investigated in foraging honeybees, *Apis mellifera*, which use both transient short-term working memory that is non-feeder specific and a feeder specific long-term reference memory.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Memory induced in a free-flying honeybee by a single learning trial lasts for days and, by three learning trials, for a lifetime.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] *Bombus terrestris audax* workers vary in their effort investment towards memorising flower locations, with smaller workers less *able* to be selective and thus less *interested* in which flowers are richer sugar sources.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Meanwhile, bigger *B. t. audax* workers have more carrying capacity and thus more reason to memorise that information, and so they do.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Slugs, *Limax flavus*, have a short-term memory of approximately 1 min and long-term memory of 1 month.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] As in humans, research with animals distinguishes between "working" or "short-term" memory from "reference" or long-term memory.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Tests of working memory evaluate memory for events that happened in the recent past, usually within the last few seconds or minutes.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Tests of reference memory evaluate memory for regularities such as "pressing a lever brings food" or "children give me peanuts".
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] This is one of the simplest tests for memory spanning a short time interval.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The test compares an animal's response to a stimulus or event on one occasion to its response on a previous occasion.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] If the second response differs consistently from the first, the animal must have remembered something about the first, unless some other factor such as motivation, sensory sensitivity, or the test stimulus has changed.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Delayed response tasks are often used to study short-term memory in animals.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Introduced by Hunter (1913), a typical delayed response task presents an animal with a stimulus such as colored light, and after a short time interval the animal chooses among alternatives that match the stimulus, or are related to the stimulus in some other way.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] In Hunter's studies, for example, a light appeared briefly in one of three goal boxes and then later the animal chose among the boxes, finding food behind the one that had been lighted.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Most research has been done with some variation of the "delayed matching-to-sample" task.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] For example, in the initial study with this task, a pigeon was presented with a flickering or steady light.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Then, a few seconds later, two pecking keys were illuminated, one with a steady light and one with a flickering light.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The bird got food if it pecked the key that matched the original stimulus.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] A commonly used variation of the matching-to-sample task requires the animal to use the initial stimulus to control a later choice between different stimuli.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] For example, if the initial stimulus is a black circle, the animal learns to choose "red" after the delay; if it is a black square, the correct choice is "green".
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Ingenious variations of this method have been used to explore many aspects of memory, including forgetting due to interference and memory for multiple items.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The radial arm maze is used to test memory for spatial location and to determine the mental processes by which location is determined.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] In a radial maze test, an animal is placed on a small platform from which paths lead in various directions to goal boxes; the animal finds food in one or more goal boxes.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Having found food in a box, the animal must return to the central platform.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The maze may be used to test both reference and working memory.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Suppose, for example, that over a number of sessions the same four arms of an eight-arm maze always lead to food.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] If in a later test session the animal goes to a box that has never been baited, this indicates a failure of reference memory.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] On the other hand, if the animal goes to a box that it has already emptied during the same test session, this indicates a failure of working memory.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Various confounding factors, such as odor cues, are carefully controlled in such experiments.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The water maze is used to test an animal's memory for spatial location and to discover how an animal is able to determine locations.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Typically the maze is a circular tank filled with water that has been made milky so that it is opaque.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Located somewhere in the maze is a small platform placed just below the surface of the water.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] When placed in the tank, the animal swims around until it finds and climbs up on the platform.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] With practice, the animal finds the platform more and more quickly.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Reference memory is assessed by removing the platform and observing the relative amount of time the animal spends swimming in the area where the platform had been located.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Visual and other cues in and around the tank may be varied to assess the animal's reliance on landmarks and the geometric relations among them.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The novel object recognition (NOR) test is an animal behavior test that is primarily used to assess memory alterations in rodents.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] It is a simple behavioral test that is based on a rodents innate exploratory behavior.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The test is divided into three phases: habituation, training/adaptation and test phase.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] During the habituation phase the animal is placed in an empty test arena.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] This is followed by the adaptation phase, where the animal is placed in the arena with two identical objects.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] In the third phase, the test phase, the animal is placed in the arena with one of the familiar objects from the previous phase and with one novel object.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Based on the rodents innate curiosity, the animals that remember the familiar object will spend more time on investigating the novel object.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Whether an animal ranges over a territory measured in square kilometers or square meters, its survival typically depends on its ability to do such things as find a food source and then return to its nest.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Sometimes such a task can be performed rather simply, for example by following a chemical trail.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Typically, however, the animal must somehow acquire and use information about locations, directions, and distances.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The following paragraphs outline some of the ways that animals do this.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Many animals travel hundreds or thousands of miles in seasonal migrations or returns to breeding grounds.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] They may be guided by the Sun, the stars, the polarization of light, magnetic cues, olfactory cues, winds, or a combination of these.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] It has been hypothesized that animals such as apes and wolves are good at spatial cognition because this skill is necessary for survival.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Some researchers argue that this ability may have diminished somewhat in dogs because humans have provided necessities such as food and shelter during some 15,000 years of domestication.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The behavior of most animals is synchronized with the earth's daily light-dark cycle.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Thus, many animals are active during the day, others are active at night, still others near dawn and dusk.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Though one might think that these "circadian rhythms" are controlled simply by the presence or absence of light, nearly every animal that has been studied has been shown to have a "biological clock" that yields cycles of activity even when the animal is in constant illumination or darkness.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Circadian rhythms are so automatic and fundamental to living things – they occur even in plants – that they are usually discussed separately from cognitive processes.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Survival often depends on an animal's ability to time intervals.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] For example, rufous hummingbirds feed on the nectar of flowers, and they often return to the same flower, but only after the flower has had enough time to replenish its supply of nectar.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] In one experiment hummingbirds fed on artificial flowers that quickly emptied of nectar but were refilled at some fixed time (e.g. twenty minutes) later.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The birds learned to come back to the flowers at about the right time, learning the refill rates of up to eight separate flowers and remembering how long ago they had visited each one.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The details of interval timing have been studied in a number of species.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] One of the most common methods is the "peak procedure".
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] In a typical experiment, a rat in an operant chamber presses a lever for food.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] A light comes on, a lever-press brings a food pellet at a fixed later time, say 10 seconds, and then the light goes off.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Timing is measured during occasional test trials on which no food is presented and the light stays on.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] On these test trials, the rat presses the lever more and more until about 10 sec and then, when no food comes, gradually stops pressing.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The time at which the rat presses most on these test trials is taken to be its estimate of the payoff time.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Experiments using the peak procedure and other methods have shown that animals can time short intervals quite exactly, can time more than one event at once, and can integrate time with spatial and other cues.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Such tests have also been used for quantitative tests of theories of animal timing, such as Gibbon's Scalar Expectancy Theory ("SET"), Killeen's Behavioral Theory of Timing, and Machado's Learning to Time model.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] No one theory has yet gained unanimous agreement.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Although tool use was long assumed to be a uniquely human trait, there is now much evidence that many animals use tools, including mammals, birds, fish, cephalopods and insects.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Discussions of tool use often involve a debate about what constitutes a "tool", and they often consider the relation of tool use to the animal's intelligence and brain size.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The bonobo starts "fishing" for the termites.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The bonobo withdraws the stick and begins eating the termites.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The bonobo eats the termites extracted with the tool.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Tool use has been reported many times in both wild and captive primates, particularly the great apes.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The use of tools by primates is varied and includes hunting (mammals, invertebrates, fish), collecting honey, processing food (nuts, fruits, vegetables and seeds), collecting water, weapons and shelter.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Research in 2007 shows that chimpanzees in the Fongoli savannah sharpen sticks to use as spears when hunting, considered the first evidence of systematic use of weapons in a species other than humans.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Other mammals that spontaneously use tools in the wild or in captivity include elephants, bears, cetaceans, sea otters and mongooses.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Several species of birds have been observed to use tools in the wild, including warblers, parrots, Egyptian vultures, brown-headed nuthatches, gulls and owls.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Some species, such as the woodpecker finch of the Galapagos Islands, use particular tools as an essential part of their foraging behavior.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] However, these behaviors are often quite inflexible and cannot be applied effectively in new situations.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] A great many species of birds build nests with a wide range of complexities, but although nest-building behaviour fulfills the criteria of some definitions of "tool-use", this is not the case with other definitions.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Several species of corvids have been trained to use tools in controlled experiments.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] One species examined extensively under laboratory conditions is the New Caledonian crow.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] One individual called "Betty" spontaneously made a wire tool to solve a novel problem.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] She was being tested to see whether she would select a wire hook rather than a straight wire to pull a little bucket of meat out of a well.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Betty tried poking the straight wire at the meat.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] After a series of failures with this direct approach, she withdrew the wire and began directing it at the bottom of the well, which was secured to its base with duct tape.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The wire soon became stuck, whereupon Betty pulled it sideways, bending it and unsticking it.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] She then inserted the hook into the well and extracted the meat.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] In all but one of 10 subsequent trials with only straight wire provided, she also made and used a hook in the same manner, but not before trying the straight wire first.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Another bird that is highly studied for its intelligence is the African Gray Parrot.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] American animal behaviorist and psychologist Irene Pepperberg vindicated that African Grays possess cognitive abilities.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Pepperberg used a bird named "Alex" in her trials and was able to prove that parrots could associate sound and meaning, demolishing long-held theories that birds were only capable of mimicking human voices.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Studies by other researchers have determined that African Grays can use deductive reasoning to correctly choose between pairs of boxes containing food and boxes that are empty.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Until Pepperberg began this research in the 1970s, few scientists had studied intelligence in parrots, and few do today.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Most inquiries have instead focused on monkeys, chimpanzees, gorillas, and dolphins, all of which are much more difficult to raise, feed, and handle.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] By the late 1980s, Alex had learned the names of more than 50 different objects, five shapes, and seven colors.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] He'd also learned what "same" and "different" mean—a step crucial in human intellectual development.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Several species of wrasses have been observed using rocks as anvils to crack bivalve (scallops, urchins and clams) shells.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] This behavior was first filmed in an orange-dotted tuskfish (*Choerodon anchorago*) in 2009 by Giacomo Bernardi.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The fish fans sand to unearth the bivalve, takes it into its mouth, swims several meters to a rock, which it then uses as an anvil by smashing the mollusc apart with sideward thrashes of the head.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] This behaviour has also been recorded in a blackspot tuskfish (*Choerodon schoenleinii*) on Australia's Great Barrier Reef, yellowhead wrasse (*Halichoeres garnoti*) in Florida and a six-bar wrasse (*Thalassoma hardwicke*) in an aquarium setting.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] These species are at opposite ends of the phylogenetic tree in this family, so this behaviour may be a deep-seated trait in all wrasses.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Cephalopods are capable of complex tasks, thus earning them the reputation of being among the smartest of invertebrates.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] For example, octopuses can open jars to get the contents inside and have remarkable ability to learn new skills from the moment they are born.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Some cephalopods are known to use coconut shells for protection or camouflage.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Cephalopod cognitive evolution is hypothesized to have been shaped primarily by predatory and foraging pressures, but a challenging mating context may also have played a role.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Ants of the species *Conomyrma bicolor* pick up stones and other small objects with their mandibles and drop them down the vertical entrances of rival colonies, allowing workers to forage for food without competition.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] It is clear that animals of quite a range of species are capable of solving problems that appear to require abstract reasoning; Wolfgang Köhler's (1917) work with chimpanzees is a famous early example.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] He observed that chimpanzees did not use trial and error to solve problems such as retrieving bananas hung out of reach.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Instead, they behaved in a manner that was "unwaveringly purposeful", spontaneously placing boxes so that they could climb to reach the fruit.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Modern research has identified similar behavior in animals usually thought of as much less intelligent, if appropriate pre-training is given.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Causal reasoning has also been observed in rooks and New Caledonian crows.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] It has been shown that Barbados bullfinches (*Loxigilla barbadensis*) from urbanized areas are better at innovative problem-solving tasks than bullfinches from rural environments, but that they did not differ in colour discrimination learning.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] A **cognitive bias** refers to a systematic pattern of deviation from norm or rationality in judgment, whereby inferences about other individuals or situations may be drawn in an illogical fashion.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Cognitive bias is sometimes illustrated by using answers to the question "Is the glass half empty or half full?".
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Choosing "half empty" is supposed to indicate pessimism whereas choosing "half full" indicates optimism.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] To test this in animals, an individual is trained to anticipate that stimulus A, e.g. a 100 Hz tone, precedes a positive event, e.g. highly desired food is delivered when a lever is pressed by the animal.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The same individual is trained to anticipate that stimulus B, e.g. a 900 Hz tone, precedes a negative event, e.g. bland food is delivered when the animal presses a lever.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The animal is then tested by being given an intermediate stimulus C, e.g. a 500 Hz tone, and observing whether the animal presses the lever associated with the positive or negative reward.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] This has been suggested to indicate whether the animal is in a positive or negative mood.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] In a study that used this approach, rats that were playfully tickled responded differently than rats that were simply handled.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The rats that had been tickled were more optimistic than the handled rats.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The authors suggested that they had demonstrated "...for the first time a link between the directly measured positive affective state and decision making under uncertainty in an animal model".
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] There is some evidence for cognitive bias in a number of species, including rats, dogs, rhesus macaques, sheep, chicks, starlings and honeybees.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The modeling of human language in animals is known as animal language research.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] In addition to the ape-language experiments mentioned above, there have also been more or less successful attempts to teach language or language-like behavior to some non-primate species, including parrots and great spotted woodpeckers.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Arguing from his own results with the animal Nim Chimpsky and his analysis of others results, Herbert Terrace criticized the idea that chimps can produce new sentences.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Shortly thereafter Louis Herman published research on artificial language comprehension in the bottlenose dolphin.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Though this sort of research has been controversial, especially among cognitive linguists, many researchers agree that many animals can understand the meaning of individual words, and that some may understand simple sentences and syntactic variations.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Elephants can remember tone, melody, and recognise more than 20 words.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Nevertheless, there is little evidence that any animal can produce new strings of symbols that correspond to new sentences.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Wolfgang Köhler is usually credited with introducing the concept of insight into experimental psychology.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Working with chimpanzees, Köhler came to dispute Edward Thorndike's theory that animals must solve problems gradually, by trial and error.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] He said that Thorndike's animals could only use trial and error because the situation precluded other forms of problem solving.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] He provided chimps with a relatively unstructured situation, and he observed sudden "ah-ha!" insightful changes of behavior, as, for example, when a chimp suddenly moved a box into position so that it could retrieve a banana.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] More recently, Asian elephants (*Elephas maximus*) were shown to exhibit similar insightful problem solving.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] A male was observed moving a box to a position where it could be stood upon to reach food that had been deliberately hung out of reach.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] A variety of studies indicates that animals are able to use and communicate quantitative information, and that some can count in a rudimentary way.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] In one study, rhesus monkeys viewed visual displays containing, for example, 1, 2, 3, or 4 items of different sorts.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] They were trained to respond to them in several ways involving numerical ordering, for example touching "1" first, "2" second and so on.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] When tested with displays containing items they had never seen before, they continued to respond to them in order.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The authors conclude that monkeys can represent the numerosities 1 to 9 at least on an ordinal scale.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Ants are able to use quantitative values and transmit this information.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] For instance, ants of several species are able to estimate quite precisely numbers of encounters with members of other colonies on their feeding territories.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Moreover, ants of some species can count up to 20 and add and subtract numbers within 5.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] This has been demonstrated using carefully crafted experiments based on measuring the time it takes for a scouting ant to pass the information to its team about the branch of an experimental maze on which food can be found.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Numeracy has been described in the yellow mealworm beetle (*Tenebrio molitor*) and the honeybee.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Western lowland gorillas given the choice between two food trays demonstrated the ability to choose the tray with more food items at a rate higher than chance after training.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] In a similar task, chimpanzees chose the option with the larger amount of food.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Salamanders given a choice between two displays with differing amounts of fruit flies, used as a food reward, reliably choose the display with more flies, as shown in a particular experiment.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Other experiments have been conducted that show animals' abilities to differentiate between non-food quantities.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] American black bears demonstrated quantity differentiation abilities in a task with a computer screen.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The bears were trained to touch a computer monitor with a paw or nose to choose a quantity of dots in one of two boxes on the screen.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Each bear was trained with reinforcement to pick a larger or smaller amount.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] During training, the bears were rewarded with food for a correct response.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] All bears performed better than what random error predicted on the trials with static, non-moving dots, indicating that they could differentiate between the two quantities.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Bottlenose dolphins have shown the ability to choose an array with fewer dots compared to one with more dots.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Experimenters set up two boards showing various numbers of dots in a poolside setup.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The dolphins were initially trained to choose the board with the fewer number of dots.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] This was done by rewarding the dolphin when it chose the board with the fewer number of dots.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] In the experimental trials, two boards were set up, and the dolphin would emerge from the water and point to one board.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The dolphins chose the arrays with fewer dots at a rate much larger than chance, indicating they can differentiate between quantities.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] A particular grey parrot, after training, has shown the ability to differentiate between the numbers zero through six using vocalizations.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] After number and vocalization training, this was done by asking the parrot how many objects there were in a display.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The parrot was able to identify the correct amount at a rate higher than chance.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Angelfish, when put in an unfamiliar environment will group together with conspecifics, an action named shoaling.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Given the choice between two groups of differing size, the angelfish will choose the larger of the two groups.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] This can be seen with a discrimination ratio of 2:1 or greater, such that, as long as one group has at least twice the fish as another group, it will join the larger one.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Monitor lizards have been shown to be capable of numeracy, and some species can distinguish among numbers up to six.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] As the cognitive ability and intelligence in non-human animals cannot be measured with verbal scales, it has been measured using a variety of methods that involve such things as habit reversal, social learning, and responses to novelty.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Principal component analysis and factor analytic studies have shown that a single factor of intelligence is responsible for 47% of the individual variance in cognitive ability measures in primates and between 55% and 60% of the variance in mice.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] These values are similar to the accepted variance in IQ explained by a similar single factor known as the general factor of intelligence in humans (40–50%).
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] However, results from a recent meta-analysis suggest that the average correlation between performance scores on various cognitive tasks is only 0.18.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Results from this study suggest that current evidence for general intelligence is weak in non-human animals.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The general factor of intelligence, or *g* factor, is a psychometric construct that summarizes the correlations observed between an individual's scores on various measures of cognitive abilities.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] It has been suggested that *g* is related to evolutionary life histories and the evolution of intelligence as well as to social learning and cultural intelligence.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Non-human models of *g* have been used in genetic and neurological research on intelligence to help understand the mechanisms behind variation in *g*.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Theory of mind is the ability to attribute mental states, e.g. intents, desires, pretending, knowledge, to oneself and others and to understand that others have desires, intentions, and perspectives that are different from one's own.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Some research with ravens provides an example of evidence for theory of mind in a non-human species.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Ravens are members of the family Corvidae, which is widely regarded as having high cognitive abilities.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] These birds have been observed to hide their food when dominant ravens are visible and audible at the same time.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Based on this observation, ravens were tested for their understanding of "seeing" as a mental state.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] In a first step, the birds protected their cache when dominants were visible but not when they could only be heard from an adjacent room.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] In the next step, they had access to a small peephole which allowed them to see into the adjacent room.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] With the peephole open, the ravens guarded their caches against discovery when they could hear dominants in the adjacent room, even when the dominant's sounds were playbacks of recordings.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The sense in which animals can be said to have self-consciousness or a self-concept has been hotly debated.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The best known research technique in this area is the mirror test devised by Gordon G.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Gallup, in which an animal's skin is marked in some way while it is asleep or sedated, and it is then allowed to see its reflection in a mirror; if the animal spontaneously directs grooming behavior towards the mark, that is taken as an indication that it is aware of itself.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Self-awareness, by this criterion, has been reported for chimpanzees and also for other great apes, the European magpie, some cetaceans and an Asian elephant, but not for monkeys.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The mirror test has been criticized by researchers because it is entirely focused on vision, the primary sense in humans, while other species rely more heavily on other senses such as the sense of smell in dogs.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] It has been suggested that metacognition in some animals provides some evidence for cognitive self-awareness.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The great apes, dolphins, and rhesus monkeys have demonstrated the ability to monitor their own mental states and use an "I don't know" response to avoid answering difficult questions.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Unlike the mirror test, which reveals awareness of the condition of one's own body, this uncertainty monitoring is thought to reveal awareness of one's internal mental state.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] A 2007 study has provided some evidence for metacognition in rats, although this interpretation has been questioned.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] These species might also be aware of the strength of their memories.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Some researchers propose that animal calls and other vocal behaviors provide evidence of consciousness.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] This idea arose from research on children's crib talk by Weir (1962) and in investigations of early speech in children by Greenfield and others (1976).
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Some such research has been done with a macaw (see Arielle).
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Instinctive drift can influence the interpretation of cognitive research.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Instinctive drift is the tendency of an animal to revert to instinctive behaviors that can interfere with learned responses.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The concept originated with Keller and Marian Breland when they taught a raccoon to put coins into a box.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The raccoon drifted to its instinctive behavior of rubbing the coins with its paws, as it would do when foraging for food.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Animal ability to process and respond to stimuli is correlated with brain size.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Small-brain animals tend to show simple behaviors that are less dependent on learning than those of large-brained animals.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Vertebrates, particularly mammals, have larger brains and complex behavior that changes with experience.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] A formula called the encephalization quotient (EQ) expresses a relationship between brain and body size; it was developed by H.J.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] When the encephalization quotient is plotted as a curve, an animal with an EQ above the curve is expected to show more cognitive ability than the average animal of its size, whereas an animal with an EQ below the curve is expected to have less.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] Various formulas been suggested, but the equation ***Ew(brain) = 0.12w(body)2/3*** has been found to fit data from a sample of mammals.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] The formula is suggestive at best, and should only be applied to non-mammals with extreme caution.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p02] For some of the other vertebrate classes, the power of 3/4 rather than 2/3 is sometimes used, and for many groups of invertebrates, the formula may not give meaningful results.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] Several experiments cannot be readily reconciled with the belief that some animal species are intelligent, insightful, or possess a theory of mind.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] Jean-Henri Fabre (1823–1915), setting the stage for all subsequent experiments of this kind, argued that insects "obey their compelling instinct, without realizing what they do".
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] For instance, to understand that she can grab her paralyzed prey by a leg instead of an antenna is utterly beyond the powers of a sand wasp.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] "Her actions are like a series of echoes each awakening the next in a settled order, which allows none to sound until the previous one has sounded." Fabre's numerous experiments led him, in turn, to the view that scientists often try to "exalt animals" instead of objectively studying them.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] Lloyd Morgan's (1852–1936) observations suggested to him that prima facie intelligent behavior in animals is often the result of either instincts or trial and error.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] For instance, most visitors watching Morgan's dog smoothly lifting a latch with the back of its head (and thereby opening a garden gate and escaping) were convinced that the dog's actions involved thinking.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] Morgan, however, carefully observed the dog's prior, random, purposeless actions and argued that they involved "continued trial and failure, until a happy effect is reached", rather than "methodical planning".
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] Thorndike (1874–1949) placed hungry cats and dogs in enclosures "from which they could escape by some simple act, such as pulling at a loop of cord".
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] Their behavior suggested to him that they did not "possess the power of rationality".
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] Most books about animal behavior, Thorndike wrote, "do not give us a psychology, but rather a eulogy of animals".
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] Although Wolfgang Köhler's 1912-1920 experiments are often cited as providing support for the animal cognition hypothesis, his book is replete with counterexamples.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] For instance, he placed chimpanzees in a situation where they could only get bananas by removing a box.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] The chimpanzee, Köhler observed, "has special difficulty in solving such problems; he often draws into a situation the strangest and most distant tools, and adopts the most peculiar methods, rather than remove a simple obstacle which could be displaced with perfect ease".
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] Moty Nissani of Wayne State University trained Burmese logging elephants to lift a lid in order to retrieve food from a bucket.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] The lid was then placed on the ground alongside the bucket (where it no longer obstructed access to the food) while the treat was simultaneously placed inside the bucket.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] All elephants continued to toss the lid before retrieving the reward, thus suggesting that elephants do not grasp simple causal relationships.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] Because the critical manipulation followed pretraining on lid removal, the result may be open to alternative interpretations involving prior training or task structure rather than causal reasoning alone.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] More generally, animal problem-solving studies can be influenced by motivation, experience, and unintended human cueing.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] Some researchers have cautioned that negative results in animal-cognition experiments may reflect features of the testing context rather than the absence of a cognitive capacity.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] Proposed limitations include low ecological validity, captivity effects, housing conditions, stress, prior experience, motivation, and unnatural developmental histories.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] One concern is that some laboratory tasks may have limited ecological validity.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] Boesch argued that the search for human cognitive uniqueness has often relied on tests with low ecological relevance and subjects with unnatural developmental histories, and that cognition may vary according to the specific challenges animals experience in their natural environments.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] Similarly, Mason argued that captivity is not a neutral "common garden" condition for comparative research, because species differ substantially in their responses to captive environments.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] Housing and environmental enrichment can also affect cognition-related measures.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] Zentall reviewed evidence that enriched environments can influence brain development, learning, impulsivity, timing, and other cognitive measures in animals.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] In some cases, wild and captive animals have been found to differ in problem-solving performance.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] For example, McCune et al. compared wild and captive Mexican jays on an extractive foraging task and found that wild individuals solved the task faster than captive conspecifics, although the two groups did not differ in subsequent learning speed after solving the task.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] These methodological concerns suggest that failures on artificial tasks should be interpreted as evidence about performance under particular experimental conditions, not necessarily as definitive evidence that a species lacks the cognitive capacity being tested.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] A traditionally common image is the *scala naturae*, the ladder of nature on which animals of different species occupy successively higher rungs, with humans typically at the top.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] However, there is some disagreement with the use of such a hierarchy, with some critics saying it may be necessary to understand specific cognitive capacities as adaptations to differing ecological niches.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] Some biologists argue that humans are not, in fact, the smartest animal, and that no animal can be characterized as the smartest, given that some animals have superior cognitive skills in certain areas.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] This contrasts with evolutionary psychologists, such as John Tooby, who assess, based on the large list of related unique characteristics that humans do possess, that humans evolved to fill a unique "cognitive niche" and can fairly be characterized as the smartest animal.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] Whether fairly or not, the performance of animals is often compared to that of humans on cognitive tasks.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] Our closest biological relatives, the great apes, tend to perform most like humans.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] Among the birds, corvids and parrots have typically been found to perform well on human-like tasks.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] Some octopodes have also been shown to exhibit a number of higher-level skills, such as tool use, but the amount of research on cephalopod intelligence is still limited.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] Baboons have been shown to be capable of recognizing words.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] The average bird or mammal, both usually endotherms, have average brain-to-body ratios ten times larger than a typical ectotherm vertebrate.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] This has contributed to a common perception amongst researchers that mammals and birds share similar "advanced" cognitive characteristics as humans, while other vertebrates such as teleost fishes are more "primitive", which has led to them being understudied.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-cognition-p03] Similarly in reptiles, a 2019 review of evidence indicates they can experience numerous emotions, such as pleasure and anxiety.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] The topic of animal consciousness is beset with a number of difficulties.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] It poses the problem of other minds in an especially severe form because animals, lacking the ability to use human language, cannot communicate their experiences.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] It is also difficult to reason objectively about the question because a denial that an animal is conscious is often taken to imply that they do not feel, their life has no value, and that harming them is not morally wrong.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] For example, the 17th-century French philosopher René Descartes is sometimes criticised for enabling animal mistreatment through his animal machine view, which claimed that only humans are conscious.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Philosophers who consider subjective experience the essence of consciousness also generally believe, as a correlate, that the existence and nature of animal consciousness can never rigorously be known.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Other thinkers, such as the cognitive scientist Douglas Hofstadter, dismiss this argument as incoherent.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Animal consciousness has been actively researched for over one hundred years.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] In 1927, the American functional psychologist Harvey Carr argued that any valid measure or understanding of awareness in animals depends on "an accurate and complete knowledge of its essential conditions in man".
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] A more recent review concluded in 1985 that "the best approach is to use experiment (especially psychophysics) and observation to trace the dawning and ontogeny of self-consciousness, perception, communication, intention, beliefs, and reflection in normal human fetuses, infants, and children".
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] In 2012, a group of neuroscientists signed the *Cambridge Declaration on Consciousness*, which "unequivocally" asserted that "humans are not unique in possessing the neurological substrates that generate consciousness.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Non-human animals, including all mammals and birds, and many other creatures, including octopuses, also possess these neural substrates." In 2024, more than 500 academics and scientists signed the *New York Declaration on Animal Consciousness*.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] The declaration states that there is strong scientific support for consciousness in mammals and birds and that it is a realistic possibility in other vertebrates and many invertebrates.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] It calls for these considerations to be taken into account in decisions affecting animals.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] The mind–body problem in philosophy examines the relationship between mind and matter, and in particular the relationship between consciousness and the brain.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] A variety of approaches have been proposed.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Dualism maintains a rigid distinction between the realms of mind and matter.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Monism maintains that there is only one kind of stuff, and that mind and matter are both aspects of it.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] The problem was addressed by pre-Aristotelian philosophers, and was famously addressed by René Descartes in the 17th century, resulting in Cartesian dualism.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Descartes believed that humans alone possess a non-physical mind, interpreting animal behaviour through a mechanistic model that denied animal consciousness.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] The rejection of the mind–body dichotomy is found in French Structuralism, and is a position that generally characterized post-war French philosophy.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] The absence of an empirically identifiable meeting point between the non-physical mind and its physical extension has proven problematic to dualism and many modern philosophers of mind maintain that the mind is not something separate from the body.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] These approaches have been particularly influential in the sciences, particularly in the fields of sociobiology, computer science, evolutionary psychology, and the neurosciences.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Epiphenomenalism is the theory in philosophy of mind that mental phenomena are caused by physical processes in the brain or that both are effects of a common cause, as opposed to mental phenomena driving the physical mechanics of the brain.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] The impression that thoughts, feelings, or sensations cause physical effects, is therefore to be understood as illusory to some extent.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] For example, it is not the feeling of fear that produces an increase in heart beat, both are symptomatic of a common physiological origin, possibly in response to a legitimate external threat.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] The history of epiphenomenalism goes back to the post-Cartesian attempt to solve the riddle of Cartesian dualism, i.e., of how mind and body could interact.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] La Mettrie, Leibniz and Spinoza all in their own way began this way of thinking.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] The idea that even if the animal were conscious nothing would be added to the production of behavior, even in animals of the human type, was first voiced by La Mettrie (1745), and then by Cabanis (1802), and was further explicated by Hodgson (1870) and Huxley (1874).
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Huxley (1874) likened mental phenomena to the whistle on a steam locomotive.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] However, epiphenomenalism flourished primarily as it found a niche among methodological or scientific behaviorism.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] In the early 1900s scientific behaviorists such as Ivan Pavlov, John B.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Skinner began the attempt to uncover laws describing the relationship between stimuli and responses, without reference to inner mental phenomena.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Instead of adopting a form of eliminativism or mental fictionalism, positions that deny that inner mental phenomena exist, a behaviorist was able to adopt epiphenomenalism in order to allow for the existence of mind.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] However, by the 1960s, scientific behaviourism met substantial difficulties and eventually gave way to the cognitive revolution.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Participants in that revolution, such as Jerry Fodor, reject epiphenomenalism and insist upon the efficacy of the mind.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Fodor even speaks of "epiphobia"—fear that one is becoming an epiphenomenalist.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Karl Popper develops in the book *The Self and Its Brain* a similar evolutionary argument.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] In his interactions with scientists and other veterinarians, Rollin asserts that he was regularly asked to prove animals are conscious and provide scientifically acceptable grounds for claiming they feel pain.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] The denial of animal consciousness by scientists has been labelled as mentophobia by Donald Griffin.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Academic reviews of the topic are equivocal, noting that the argument that animals have at least simple conscious thoughts and feelings has strong support, but some critics continue to question how reliably animal mental states can be determined.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] A refereed journal *Animal Sentience* launched in 2016 by the Institute of Science and Policy of The Humane Society of the United States is devoted to research on this and related topics.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Consciousness is an elusive concept that presents many difficulties when attempts are made to define it.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Its study has progressively become an interdisciplinary challenge for numerous researchers, including ethologists, neurologists, cognitive neuroscientists, philosophers, psychologists and psychiatrists.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] In 1976, Richard Dawkins wrote, "The evolution of the capacity to simulate seems to have culminated in subjective consciousness.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Why this should have happened is, to me, the most profound mystery facing modern biology." In 2004, eight neuroscientists felt it was still too soon for a definition.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] We have no idea how consciousness emerges from the physical activity of the brain and we do not know whether consciousness can emerge from non-biological systems, such as computers...
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] At this point the reader will expect to find a careful and precise definition of consciousness.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Consciousness has not yet become a scientific term that can be defined in this way.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] in many different and often ambiguous ways.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Precise definitions of different aspects of consciousness will emerge ... but to make precise definitions at this stage is premature.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Consciousness is sometimes defined as the quality or state of being aware of an external object or something within oneself.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] It has been defined somewhat vaguely as: subjectivity, awareness, sentience, the ability to experience or to feel, wakefulness, having a sense of selfhood, and the executive control system of the mind.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Despite the difficulty in definition, many philosophers believe that there is a broadly shared underlying intuition about what consciousness is.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Sentience (the ability to feel, perceive, or to experience subjectivity) is not the same as self-awareness (being aware of oneself as an individual).
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] The mirror test is sometimes considered to be an operational test for self-awareness, and the handful of animals that have passed it are often considered to be self-aware.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] It remains debatable whether recognition of one's mirror image can be properly construed to imply full self-awareness, particularly given that robots are being constructed which appear to pass the test.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] However, this view has been criticized because consciousness has yet to be shown to be a process, and the so-called "hard problem" of relating consciousness directly to brain activity remains elusive.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Since Descartes's proposal of dualism, it became general consensus that the mind had become a matter of philosophy and that science was not able to penetrate the issue of consciousness – that consciousness was outside of space and time.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] However, in recent decades many scholars have begun to move toward a science of consciousness.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Antonio Damasio and Gerald Edelman are two neuroscientists who have led the move to neural correlates of the self and of consciousness.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Damasio has demonstrated that emotions and their biological foundation play a critical role in high level cognition, and Edelman has created a framework for analyzing consciousness through a scientific outlook.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] The current problem consciousness researchers face involves explaining how and why consciousness arises from neural computation.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] In his research on this problem, Edelman has developed a theory of consciousness, in which he has coined the terms primary consciousness and secondary consciousness.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Eugene Linden, author of *The Parrot's Lament* suggests there are many examples of animal behavior and intelligence that surpass what people would suppose to be the boundary of animal consciousness.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Linden contends that in many of these documented examples, a variety of animal species exhibit behavior that can only be attributed to emotion, and to a level of consciousness that we would normally ascribe only to our own species.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Consciousness in mammals (including humans) is an aspect of the mind generally thought to comprise qualities such as subjectivity, sentience, and the ability to perceive the relationship between oneself and one's environment.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] It is a subject of much research in philosophy of mind, psychology, neuroscience, and cognitive science.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Some philosophers divide consciousness into phenomenal consciousness, which is subjective experience itself, and access consciousness, which refers to the global availability of information to processing systems in the brain.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Phenomenal consciousness has many different experienced qualities, often referred to as qualia.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Phenomenal consciousness is usually consciousness *of* something or *about* something, a property known as intentionality in philosophy of mind.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] In humans, there are three common methods of studying consciousness: verbal reporting, behavioural demonstrations, and neural correlation with conscious activity, though these can only be generalized to non-human taxa with varying degrees of difficulty.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] In a new study conducted in rhesus monkeys, Ben-Haim and his team used a process dissociation approach that predicted opposite behavioral outcomes for the two modes of perception.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] They found that monkeys displayed exactly the same opposite behavioral outcomes as humans when they were aware or unaware of the stimuli presented.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] The sense in which animals (or human infants) can be said to have consciousness or a self-concept has been hotly debated; it is often referred to as the debate over animal minds.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Gallup, in which the skin of an animal (or human infant) is marked, while they are asleep or sedated, with a mark that cannot be seen directly but is visible in a mirror.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] The animals are then allowed to see their reflection in a mirror; if the animal spontaneously directs grooming behaviour towards the mark, that is taken as an indication that they are aware of themselves.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Over the past 30 years, many studies have found evidence that animals recognise themselves in mirrors.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Until recently, it was thought that self-recognition was absent in animals without a neocortex, and was restricted to mammals with large brains and well-developed social cognition.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] However, in 2008, a study of self-recognition in corvids reported significant results for magpies.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Mammals and birds inherited the same brain components from their last common ancestor nearly 300 million years ago, and have since independently evolved and formed significantly different brain types.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] The results of the mirror and mark tests showed that neocortex-less magpies are capable of understanding that a mirror image belongs to their own body.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] The findings show that magpies respond in the mirror and mark tests in a manner similar to apes, dolphins and elephants.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] The magpies were chosen to study based on their empathy and lifestyle, a possible precursor to their ability to develop self-awareness.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] For chimpanzees, the occurrence is about 75% in young adults and considerably less in young and old individuals.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] For monkeys, non-primate mammals, and a number of bird species, exploration of the mirror and social displays were observed.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Hints at mirror-induced self-directed behavior have been obtained.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] According to a 2019 study, cleaner wrasses have become the first fish ever observed to pass the mirror test.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] However, the test's inventor Gordon Gallup has said that the fish were most likely trying to scrape off a perceived parasite on another fish and that they did not demonstrate self-recognition.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] The authors of the study responded that because the fish checked themselves in the mirror before and after the scraping, this meant that the fish had self-awareness and recognized that their reflections belonged to their own bodies.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] The mirror test has attracted controversy among some researchers because it is entirely focused on vision, the primary sense in humans, while other species rely more heavily on other senses such as the olfactory sense in dogs.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] A study in 2015 showed that the "sniff test of self-recognition (STSR)" provides evidence of self-awareness in dogs.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Another approach to determine whether a non-human animal is conscious derives from passive speech research with a macaw (see Arielle).
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Some researchers propose that by passively listening to an animal's voluntary speech, it is possible to learn about the thoughts of another creature and to determine that the speaker is conscious.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] This type of research was originally used to investigate a child's crib speech by Weir (1962) and in investigations of early speech in children by Greenfield and others (1976).
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Zipf's law might be able to be used to indicate if a given dataset of animal communication indicate an intelligent natural language.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Some researchers have used this algorithm to study bottlenose dolphin language.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Further arguments revolve around the ability of animals to feel pain or suffering, which implies consciousness.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] If animals can be shown to suffer in ways comparable to humans, ethical arguments against human suffering may be extended to animals.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Some scholars argue that pain can be inferred from non-purposeful or maladaptive reactions to negative stimuli.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] One such reaction is transmarginal inhibition, a phenomenon observed in both humans and some animals that resembles mental breakdown.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Cosmologist Carl Sagan argues that humans often deny animal suffering to justify practices such as enslavement, experimentation, and consumption.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] He contends that behavioral similarities between humans and other animals challenge such denials.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] John Webster, professor of animal husbandry, argues that suffering is not dependent on intelligence or brain size.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] He states that sentient animals actively seek pleasure and display behaviors indicating enjoyment, such as basking in the sun.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] However, there is no consensus about which organisms are capable of experiencing pain.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Philosopher Justin Leiber discusses varying views: Michel de Montaigne attributes consciousness to insects and even plants, while Peter Singer and Samuel Clarke deny it in simpler organisms like sponges.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Singer places the boundary somewhere between shrimp and oysters, while others speculate about insects, spiders, or tapeworms.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Some critics draw comparisons to plants, questioning whether a focus on animal suffering is entirely distinct.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Science writer Carol Kaesuk Yoon describes how plants, when damaged, initiate chemical defenses and repair processes, though these do not necessarily imply consciousness.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Cognitive bias in animals is a pattern of deviation in judgment, whereby inferences about other animals and situations may be drawn in an illogical fashion.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Individuals create their own "subjective social reality" from their perception of the input.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] It refers to the question "Is the glass half empty or half full?", used as an indicator of optimism or pessimism.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Cognitive biases have been shown in a wide range of species including rats, dogs, rhesus macaques, sheep, chicks, starlings and honeybees.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] The neuroscientist Joseph LeDoux advocates avoiding terms derived from human subjective experience when discussing brain functions in animals.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] For example, the common practice of calling brain circuits that detect and respond to threats "fear circuits" implies that these circuits are responsible for feelings of fear.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] LeDoux argues that Pavlovian fear conditioning should be renamed Pavlovian threat conditioning to avoid the implication that "fear" is being acquired in rats or humans.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Key to his theoretical change is the notion of survival functions mediated by survival circuits, the purpose of which is to keep organisms alive rather than to make emotions.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] For example, defensive survival circuits exist to detect and respond to threats.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] While all organisms can do this, only organisms that can be conscious of their own brain's activities can feel fear.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Fear is a conscious experience and occurs the same way as any other kind of conscious experience: via cortical circuits that allow attention to certain forms of brain activity.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] LeDoux argues the only differences between an emotional and non-emotion state of consciousness are the underlying neural ingredients that contribute to the state.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Neuroscience is the scientific study of the nervous system.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] It is a highly active interdisciplinary science that collaborates with many other fields.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] The scope of neuroscience has broadened recently to include molecular, cellular, developmental, structural, functional, evolutionary, computational, and medical aspects of the nervous system.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Theoretical studies of neural networks are being complemented with techniques for imaging sensory and motor tasks in the brain.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] According to a 2008 paper, neuroscience explanations of psychological phenomena currently have a "seductive allure", and "seem to generate more public interest" than explanations which do not contain neuroscientific information.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] They found that subjects who were not neuroscience experts "judged that explanations with logically irrelevant neuroscience information were more satisfying than explanations without.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] The neural correlates of consciousness constitute the minimal set of neuronal events and mechanisms sufficient for a specific conscious percept.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Neuroscientists use empirical approaches to discover neural correlates of subjective phenomena.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] The set should be *minimal* because, if the brain is sufficient to give rise to any given conscious experience, the question is which of its components is necessary to produce it.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Visual sense and representation was reviewed in 1998 by Francis Crick and Christof Koch.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] They concluded sensory neuroscience can be used as a bottom-up approach to studying consciousness, and suggested experiments to test various hypotheses in this research stream.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] A feature that distinguishes humans from most animals is that we are not born with an extensive repertoire of behavioral programs that would enable us to survive on our own ("physiological prematurity").
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] To compensate for this, we have an unmatched ability to learn, i.e., to consciously acquire such programs by imitation or exploration.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Once consciously acquired and sufficiently exercised, these programs can become automated to the extent that their execution happens beyond the realms of our awareness.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Take, as an example, the incredible fine motor skills exerted in playing a Beethoven piano sonata or the sensorimotor coordination required to ride a motorcycle along a curvy mountain road.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Such complex behaviors are possible only because a sufficient number of the subprograms involved can be executed with minimal or even suspended conscious control.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] In fact, the conscious system may actually interfere somewhat with these automated programs.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] The growing ability of neuroscientists to manipulate neurons using methods from molecular biology in combination with optical tools depends on the simultaneous development of appropriate behavioural assays and model organisms amenable to large-scale genomic analysis and manipulation.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] A combination of such fine-grained neuronal analysis in animals with ever more sensitive psychophysical and brain imaging techniques in humans, complemented by the development of a robust theoretical predictive framework, will hopefully lead to a rational understanding of consciousness.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] The neocortex is a part of the brain of mammals.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] It consists of the grey matter, or neuronal cell bodies and unmyelinated fibers, surrounding the deeper white matter (myelinated axons) in the cerebrum.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] The neocortex is smooth in rodents and other small mammals, whereas in primates and other larger mammals it has deep grooves and wrinkles.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] These folds increase the surface area of the neocortex considerably without taking up too much more volume.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Also, neurons within the same wrinkle have more opportunity for connectivity, while neurons in different wrinkles have less opportunity for connectivity, leading to compartmentalization of the cortex.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] The neocortex is divided into frontal, parietal, occipital, and temporal lobes, which perform different functions.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] For example, the occipital lobe contains the primary visual cortex, and the temporal lobe contains the primary auditory cortex.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Further subdivisions or areas of neocortex are responsible for more specific cognitive processes.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] The neocortex is the newest part of the cerebral cortex to evolve (hence the prefix "neo"); the other parts of the cerebral cortex are the paleocortex and archicortex, collectively known as the allocortex.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] In humans, 90% of the cerebral cortex is neocortex.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Researchers have argued that consciousness in mammals arises in the neocortex, and therefore by extension used to argue that consciousness cannot arise in animals which lack a neocortex.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] For instance, evidence suggests the pallium in bird brains to be functionally equivalent to the mammalian cerebral cortex as a basis of consciousness.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Attention is the cognitive process of selectively concentrating on one aspect of the environment while ignoring other things.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Attention has also been referred to as the allocation of processing resources.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Attention also has variations amongst cultures.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Voluntary attention develops in specific cultural and institutional contexts through engagement in cultural activities with more competent community members.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Most experiments show that one neural correlate of attention is enhanced firing.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] If a neuron has a certain response to a stimulus when the animal is not attending to the stimulus, then when the animal does attend to the stimulus, the neuron's response will be enhanced even if the physical characteristics of the stimulus remain the same.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] In many cases attention produces changes in the EEG.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Many animals, including humans, produce gamma waves (40–60 Hz) when focusing attention on a particular object or activity.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Extended consciousness is an animal's autobiographical self-perception.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] It is thought to arise in the brains of animals which have a substantial capacity for memory and reason.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] It does not necessarily require language.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] The perception of a historic and future self arises from a stream of information from the immediate environment and from neural structures related to memory.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] The concept was popularised by Antonio Damasio and is used in biological psychology.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Extended consciousness is said to arise in structures in the human brain described as *image spaces* and *dispositional spaces*.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Image spaces imply areas where sensory impressions of all types are processed, including the focused awareness of the core consciousness.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Dispositional spaces include convergence zones, which are networks in the brain where memories are processed and recalled, and where knowledge is merged with immediate experience.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Metacognition is defined as "cognition about cognition", or "knowing about knowing." It can take many forms; it includes knowledge about when and how to use particular strategies for learning or for problem solving.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] It has been suggested that metacognition in some animals provides evidence for cognitive self-awareness.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] There are generally two components of metacognition: knowledge about cognition, and regulation of cognition.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Writings on metacognition can be traced back at least as far as *De Anima* and the *Parva Naturalia* of the Greek philosopher Aristotle.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Metacognologists believe that the ability to consciously think about thinking is unique to sapient species and indeed is one of the definitions of sapience.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] There is evidence that rhesus monkeys and apes can make accurate judgments about the strengths of their memories of fact and monitor their own uncertainty, while attempts to demonstrate metacognition in birds have been inconclusive.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] A 2007 study provided some evidence for metacognition in rats, but further analysis suggested that they may have been following simple operant conditioning principles, or a behavioral economic model.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Mirror neurons are neurons that fire both when an animal acts and when the animal observes the same action performed by another.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Thus, the neuron "mirrors" the behavior of the other, as though the observer were themselves acting.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Such neurons have been directly observed in primate and other species including birds.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] The function of the mirror system is a subject of much speculation.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Many researchers in cognitive neuroscience and cognitive psychology consider that this system provides the physiological mechanism for the perception action coupling (see the common coding theory).
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] They argue that mirror neurons may be important for understanding the actions of other people, and for learning new skills by imitation.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Some researchers also speculate that mirror systems may simulate observed actions, and thus contribute to theory of mind skills, while others relate mirror neurons to language abilities.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Neuroscientists such as Marco Iacoboni (UCLA) have argued that mirror neuron systems in the human brain help us understand the actions and intentions of other people.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] In a study published in March 2005, Iacoboni and his colleagues reported that mirror neurons could discern if another person who was picking up a cup of tea planned to drink from it or clear it from the table.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] In addition, Iacoboni and a number of other researchers have argued that mirror neurons are the neural basis of the human capacity for emotions such as empathy.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Ramachandran has speculated that mirror neurons may provide the neurological basis of self-awareness.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Consciousness is likely an evolved adaptation since it meets George Williams' criteria of species universality, complexity, and functionality, and it is a trait that apparently increases fitness.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Opinions are divided as to where in biological evolution consciousness emerged and about whether or not consciousness has survival value.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] It has been argued that consciousness emerged (i) exclusively with the first humans, (ii) exclusively with the first mammals, (iii) independently in mammals and birds, or (iv) with the first reptiles.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Donald Griffin suggests in his book *Animal Minds* a gradual evolution of consciousness.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Each of these scenarios raises the question of the possible survival value of consciousness.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] In his paper "Evolution of consciousness," John Eccles argues that special anatomical and physical adaptations of the mammalian cerebral cortex gave rise to consciousness.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Once in place, this recursive circuitry may well have provided a basis for the subsequent development of many of the functions that consciousness facilitates in higher organisms, as outlined by Bernard J.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Richard Dawkins suggested that humans evolved consciousness in order to make themselves the subjects of thought.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Daniel Povinelli suggests that large, tree-climbing apes evolved consciousness to take into account one's own mass when moving safely among tree branches.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Consistent with this hypothesis, Gordon Gallup found that chimpanzees and orangutans, but not little monkeys or terrestrial gorillas, demonstrated self-awareness in mirror tests.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] The concept of consciousness can refer to voluntary action, awareness, or wakefulness.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] However, even voluntary behaviour involves unconscious mechanisms.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Many cognitive processes take place in the cognitive unconscious, unavailable to conscious awareness.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Some behaviours are conscious when learned but then become unconscious, seemingly automatic.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Learning, especially implicitly learning a skill, can take place outside of consciousness.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] For example, plenty of people know how to turn right when they ride a bike, but very few can accurately explain how they actually do so.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Neural Darwinism is a large scale theory of brain function initially proposed in 1978 by the American biologist Gerald Edelman.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Primary consciousness can be defined as simple awareness that includes perception and emotion.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] As such, it is ascribed to most animals.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] By contrast, secondary consciousness depends on and includes such features as self-reflective awareness, abstract thinking, volition and metacognition.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Edelman's theory focuses on two nervous system organizations: the brainstem and limbic systems on one side and the thalamus and cerebral cortex on the other side.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] The brain stem and limbic system take care of essential body functioning and survival, while the thalamocortical system receives signals from sensory receptors and sends out signals to voluntary muscles such as those of the arms and legs.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] The theory asserts that the connection of these two systems during evolution helped animals learn adaptive behaviors.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Other scientists have argued against Edelman's theory, instead suggesting that primary consciousness might have emerged with the basic vegetative systems of the brain.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] This is based on neurological data showing the thalamic, hippocampal, orbitofrontal, insula, and midbrain sites are the key to consciousness of thirst.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] These scientists also point out that the cortex might not be as important to primary consciousness as some neuroscientists have believed.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Some researchers argue that systematic disruption of cortical regions in nonhuman animals does not prevent consciousness, and that reports of consciousness in children born without a cortex are consistent with this view.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] On this account, brainstem mechanisms are proposed to play a primary role in consciousness.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Still, these scientists concede that higher order consciousness does involve the cortex and complex communication between different areas of the brain.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] While animals with primary consciousness have long-term memory, they lack explicit narrative, and, at best, can only deal with the immediate scene in the remembered present.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] While they still have an advantage over animals lacking such ability, evolution has brought forth a growing complexity in consciousness, particularly in mammals.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Animals with this complexity are said to have secondary consciousness.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Secondary consciousness is seen in animals with semantic capabilities, such as the four great apes.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] It is present in its richest form in the human species, which is unique in possessing complex language made up of syntax and semantics.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] The ability of an animal to relate a present complex scene to their own previous history of learning conferred an adaptive evolutionary advantage.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] At much later evolutionary epochs, further re-entrant circuits appeared that linked semantic and linguistic performance to categorical and conceptual memory systems.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] This development enabled the emergence of secondary consciousness.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Ursula Voss of the Universität Bonn believes that the theory of protoconsciousness may serve as adequate explanation for self-recognition found in birds, as they would develop secondary consciousness during REM sleep.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] She added that many types of birds have very sophisticated language systems.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Don Kuiken of the University of Alberta finds such research interesting as well as if we continue to study consciousness with animal models (with differing types of consciousness), we would be able to separate the different forms of reflectiveness found in today's world.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] For the advocates of the idea of a secondary consciousness, self-recognition serves as a critical component and a key defining measure.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] What is most interesting then, is the evolutionary appeal that arises with the concept of self-recognition.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] In non-human species and in children, the mirror test (see above) has been used as an indicator of self-awareness.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] A 2020 paper by Jonathan Birch, Alexandra K.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] Clayton outlined a multidimensional approach to animal consciousness, intended to account for variation in conscious experience across species.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] The authors propose that consciousness may not be meaningfully represented along a single continuum, and instead suggest five distinct dimensions for constructing species-specific profiles.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p01] The authors suggest that this framework could facilitate comparative studies of consciousness in different taxa, including mammals, birds, and cephalopods.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p02] In 2012, a group of neuroscientists attending a conference on "Consciousness in Human and non-Human Animals" at the University of Cambridge in the UK, signed the *Cambridge Declaration on Consciousness* (see box on the right).
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p02] In 2024, a conference on "The Emerging Science of Animal Consciousness" at New York University produced *The New York Declaration on Animal Consciousness*.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p02] A common image is the *scala naturae*, the ladder of nature on which animals of different species occupy successively higher rungs, with humans typically at the top.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p02] A more useful approach has been to recognize that different animals may have different kinds of cognitive processes, which are better understood in terms of the ways in which they are cognitively adapted to their different ecological niches, than by positing any kind of hierarchy.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p02] Dogs were previously listed as non-self-aware animals.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p02] Traditionally, self-consciousness was evaluated via the mirror test.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p02] But dogs, and many other animals, are not (as) visually oriented.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p02] The study further suggests adopting a species-specific, rather than anthropocentric, approach to research on animal consciousness.This study has been confirmed by another study.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p02] Research with captive grey parrots, especially Irene Pepperberg's work with an individual named Alex, has demonstrated they possess the ability to associate simple human words with meanings, and to intelligently apply the abstract concepts of shape, colour, number, zero-sense, etc.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p02] According to Pepperberg and other scientists, they perform many cognitive tasks at the level of dolphins, chimpanzees, and even human toddlers.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p02] Another notable African grey is N'kisi, which in 2004 was said to have a vocabulary of over 950 words which she used in creative ways.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p02] For example, when Jane Goodall visited N'kisi in his New York home, he greeted her with "Got a chimp?" because he had seen pictures of her with chimpanzees in Africa.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p02] In 2011, research led by Dalila Bovet of Paris West University Nanterre La Défense, demonstrated grey parrots were able to coordinate and collaborate with each other to an extent.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p02] They were able to solve problems such as two birds having to pull strings at the same time to obtain food.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p02] In another example, one bird stood on a perch to release a food-laden tray, while the other pulled the tray out from the test apparatus.
[src:animal-assisted-therapy/animal-consciousness-p02] The birds were observed waiting for their partners to perform the necessary actions so their behaviour could be synchronized.
